{"title_page": "Shooting of Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez", "text_new": "{{use MDY dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n | Event_Name     = Shooting of Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez\n | Image_Name     = File:Mexican-American border at Nogales.jpg\n | Imagesize      = 300\n | Image_Alt      = \n | Image_Caption  = View of the international border from the top of the U.S. Customs port of entry facility in Nogales, Arizona (January 2007)\n | Thumb_Time     =\n | AKA            =\n | Participants   = \n | Location       = [[Nogales, Arizona]], [[United States]]<br>[[Nogales, Sonora]], [[Mexico]]\n | Date           = October 10, 2012\n | Deaths        = 1\n | Result         = [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] Agent Lonnie Swartz acquitted of murder\n | URL            =\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mexican Drug War}}\n\nOn October 10, 2012, at  the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] near [[Nogales, Arizona]], [[U.S. Border Patrol]] agent '''Lonnie Swartz''' fired 16 shots<ref name=\"azcentral-notguilty-2018-04-23\" /> at teenager '''Jos\u00e9 Antonio Elena Rodr\u00edguez''' (born January 4, 1996), killing him,<ref name=shots>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/magazine/10-shots-across-the-border.html|title=10 Shots Across the Border|last=Binelli|first=Mark|date=2016-03-03|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref> on the grounds that [[Criminal rock throwing|young men threw rocks]] at him and other law enforcement agents.\n\nRodriguez was hit 10 times from behind by Swartz's shots.<ref name=\"CarranzaTeen\">{{cite news|last1=Carranza|first1=Rafael|last2=O'Dell|first2=Rob|title=Border Patrol agent Lonnie Swartz found not guilty in cross-border slaying of Mexican teen|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2018/04/23/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-found-not-guilty-cross-border-slaying-mexican-teen/544197002/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|newspaper=[[The Arizona Republic]]|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"GUARDIAN1\">{{cite news |last=Yuhas|first=Alan|date=May 31, 2015|title=Justice for Jos\u00e9? Border shooting of Mexican teen raises constitutional issue|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/31/jose-antonio-us-mexico-border-shooting-constitutional-rights|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR1\">{{cite news |last=Burnett|first=John|date=October 9, 2015|title=In A First, Border Agent Indicted For Killing Mexican Teen Across Fence|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/10/09/446866267/in-a-first-border-agent-indicted-for-killing-mexican-teen-across-fence|website=[[NPR]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Swartz was charged with [[second degree murder]] for the killing. He was acquitted on the murder charge and the jury failed to reach a verdict on lesser charges.\n\n==Incident==\nAround 11:30 p.m. on Wednesday, October 10, 2012, John Zu\u00f1iga, a police officer in [[Nogales, Arizona]],  received a call reporting \"suspicious activity\" on International Street, a road running directly along the  border. Getting to the scene, Zu\u00f1iga heard from another police officer from Nogales, Quinardo Garci, that  two men carrying \"bundles taped to their backs\" had climbed the fence into the United States. Identifying the bundles, on the basis of similar incidents in the past, as most probably containing [[marijuana]], they called out for back up.<ref name=shots/>\n\nAfter several [[United States Border Patrol|Border Patrol]] and [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|Customs]] agents arrived, they saw the two men scaling the fence back into Mexico, empty-handed and with nothing on their backs. They commanded the two men to climb back down. At that time, Garcia and Zu\u00f1iga stated in their reports that they saw \"rocks flying through the air\"<ref name=\"tucson.com\">{{cite news|title=Border agent's murder trial postponed|url=http://tucson.com/news/border-agent-s-murder-trial-postponed/article_561ac027-ef47-5d29-8d01-9c073669afff.html|date=2016-01-05|first=Perla |last=Trevizo|newspaper=Arizona Daily Star|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> at the assorted agents and also heard \"gunfire\", although they were unable to identify its source.<ref name=shots/><ref name=\"CarranzaTeen\"/> \n\nIn the days following the incident, the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] agency stated that\n:After verbal commands from agents to cease [assaulting the agents with rocks] were ignored, one agent then discharged his service firearm. One of the subjects appeared to have been hit.\n\nThe person hit was Jos\u00e9 Antonio Elena Rodr\u00edguez, a 16-year old resident of [[Nogales, Sonora|Nogales, Mexico]]. He was unarmed, standing on the Mexican side of the border on a sidewalk on Calle Internacional street, in front of a doctor's office, below a sign reading \"Medical Emergencies\" in Spanish. He was hit from behind by 10 bullets.<ref name=\"GUARDIAN1\"/> The [[autopsy]] revealed that gunshot wounds to the head, [[lung]]s, and [[artery|arteries]] killed him.<ref name=shots/><ref name=\"NPR1\"/>\n\n==Trial==\nU.S. Border Patrol agent Lonnie Ray Swartz was charged with [[second degree murder]] for the killing of Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez. There had been a number of similar incidents in the preceding decade, but this was the first time a US law enforcement officer was charged in relation to a killing that took part across the US\u2013Mexican border.<ref name=NPR1 /><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis|first=Charles|date=January 4, 2015|title=U.S. Customs and Border Protection Has Killed Nearly 50 People in 10 Years. Most Were Unarmed.|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120687/border-patrol-officers-get-impunity-anonymity-immigrant-killings|newspaper=[[The New Republic]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the trial, which began in late 2015, the defendant said he had used deadly force because Rodriguez \"had been throwing rocks\".<ref name=shots/> A witness testified that Rodr\u00edguez was not throwing rocks at the law enforcement officers but prosecutors acknowledged that Rodr\u00edguez was throwing rocks across the border and went on to state that \"he did not deserve to die\" for this.<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\">{{cite news|title=Mistrial announced for U.S. border agent linked to teenager's fatal shooting|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mistrial-us-border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-manslaughter-charges-today-2018-04-23/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|publisher=CBS News|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> The U.S. Customs and Border Protection refused to release surveillance-camera footage of the incident.<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/>\n\nAfter the testimony of the director of the medical examiner in [[Miami-Dade County]], Florida, Emma Lew, who stated that Swartz's first shot \"likely hit the boy in the middle of his back as he was running,\" the prosecution rested its case in the trial on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/040518_swartz_trial/swartz-trial-defense-struggles-with-first-witness-after-prosecution-rests/|title=\nSwartz trial: Defense struggles with first witness after prosecution rests|first=Paul|last= Ingram|publisher=Tucson Sentinel|date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2018, Swartz was acquitted of the charge for second-degree murder; the jury was [[deadlock]]ed on lesser charges.<ref name=\"azcentral-notguilty-2018-04-23\">{{Cite news|last1=Carranza |first1=Rafael  |last2=O'Dell |first2=Rob |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/2018/04/23/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-found-not-guilty-cross-border-slaying-mexican-teen/544197002/|title=Border Patrol agent Lonnie Swartz found not guilty in cross-border slaying of Mexican teen|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=April 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n==Aftermath==\nThe judge presiding on the trial, [[Raner Collins]], declared a [[mistrial]]. The head of the Tucson union for Border Patrol officers, stated, after the jury's decision was announced, that \"justice was properly served\" and that the union was \"pretty happy with it\".<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/> \n\nAfter the jury's decision was reported, protesters gathered outside the federal courthouse in downtown Tucson late Monday afternoon, on 23  April,<ref name=blocked>{{cite news|date=16 April 2018|title=Protesters block I-10 on/off ramps for several hours|url=https://www.kold.com/story/37967210/border-patrol-shooting-lonnie-swarts-jose-elena-rodriguez/|work=[[KOLD-TV|Kold TV News]] |location=Tucson, Arizona|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and blocked off the intersection in front of it. Among those participating in the protest was the mother of Carlos LaMadrid, another Mexican teen who had been shot and killed by Border Patrol agents (in 2011).<ref name=retried>{{Cite news|last1=Carranza |first1=Rafael |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2018/05/11/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-retried-death-jose-antonio-elena-rodriguez/602687002/|title=Border Patrol agent will be retried in fatal cross-border shooting of teen|date=May 11, 2018|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=June 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n==Retrials==\nOn Friday 13 December 2019, Assistant U.S. Attorney May Sue Feldmeier announced that prosecutors would seek a retrial on the two lesser charges<ref group=note>The lesser charges were for voluntary and involuntary manslaughter.</ref> against Swartz, who waived his right to appear in court. The case's presiding judge, U.S. District Judge Raner C. Collins, set the start of the new trial for 23 October 2020, with a motion hearing scheduled in July 2020.<ref name=retried/> \n\nIn 2919, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] filed a suit in the federal district court in Tucson on behalf of the family of Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez  against the border patrol agent who shot and killed him seeking  [[civil damages]]. In a preliminary hearing on Monday 9 December 2019, a video reconstruction of the shooting, including portions of video clips shot by two border cameras operated by the Border Patrol,<ref group=note>According to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' report, one camera  was mounted on a pole near the scene of the shooting, just west of the primary port of entry in Nogales, while the other was mounted about 2,500 feet away and east of the port of entry.</ref> was shown by the prosecution. Defense attorneys asked the judge not to permit the video reconstruction to be shown at the trial, arguing that \"the video evidence is unreliable.\"<ref name=video>{{cite news |last= O'Dell|first=Rob|date=14 December 2019 |title=Video of teen killed by Border Patrol agent shows he was facedown on ground when shots fired |url=https://eu.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2017/06/19/nogales-teen-elena-rodriguez-ground-when-shot-border-agent-lonnie-swartz/408088001/|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Review of similar incidents==\nA 2013 review by the Police Executive Research Forum (PERF) reviewed 67 shooting incidents that resulted in 19 people dying, during the period from January 2010 through October 2012. The review found agents guilty of criminal conduct in 3 of the incidents. Two agents faced disciplinary action in the form of an \"oral reprimand\".<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of killings by law enforcement officers in the United States, October 2012]]\n*''[[Hernandez v. Mesa]]''\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}} \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{cite journal |last=The Police Executive Research Forum |first=|url=https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/documents/PERFReport.pdf|date=February 2013 |title=U.S. Customs and Border Protection Use of Force Review: Cases and Policies|journal= |volume=|pages=|bibcode= |doi=}}\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodriguez, Killing of Jos\u00e9}}\n\n[[Category:International incidents]]\n[[Category:People shot dead by law enforcement officers]]\n[[Category:Mexico\u2013United States border]]\n[[Category:2012 in Arizona]]\n[[Category:2012 in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:October 2012 events in North America]]\n[[Category:Nogales, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Nogales, Sonora]]\n[[Category:October 2012 events in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{use MDY dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n | Event_Name     = Shooting of Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez\n | Image_Name     = File:Mexican-American border at Nogales.jpg\n | Imagesize      = 300\n | Image_Alt      = \n | Image_Caption  = View of the international border from the top of the U.S. Customs port of entry facility in Nogales, Arizona (January 2007)\n | Thumb_Time     =\n | AKA            =\n | Participants   = \n | Location       = [[Nogales, Arizona]], [[United States]]<br>[[Nogales, Sonora]], [[Mexico]]\n | Date           = October 10, 2012\n | Deaths        = 1\n | Result         = [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] Agent Lonnie Swartz acquitted of murder\n | URL            =\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mexican Drug War}}\n\nOn October 10, 2012, at  the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]] near [[Nogales, Arizona]], [[U.S. Border Patrol]] agent '''Lonnie Swartz''' fired 16 shots<ref name=\"azcentral-notguilty-2018-04-23\" /> at teenager '''Jos\u00e9 Antonio Elena Rodr\u00edguez''' (born January 4, 1996), killing him,<ref name=shots>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/magazine/10-shots-across-the-border.html|title=10 Shots Across the Border|last=Binelli|first=Mark|date=2016-03-03|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref> on the grounds that [[Criminal rock throwing|young men threw rocks]] at him and other law enforcement agents.\n\nRodriguez was hit 10 times from behind by Swartz's shots.<ref name=\"CarranzaTeen\">{{cite news|last1=Carranza|first1=Rafael|last2=O'Dell|first2=Rob|title=Border Patrol agent Lonnie Swartz found not guilty in cross-border slaying of Mexican teen|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2018/04/23/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-found-not-guilty-cross-border-slaying-mexican-teen/544197002/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|newspaper=[[The Arizona Republic]]|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"GUARDIAN1\">{{cite news |last=Yuhas|first=Alan|date=May 31, 2015|title=Justice for Jos\u00e9? Border shooting of Mexican teen raises constitutional issue|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/31/jose-antonio-us-mexico-border-shooting-constitutional-rights|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR1\">{{cite news |last=Burnett|first=John|date=October 9, 2015|title=In A First, Border Agent Indicted For Killing Mexican Teen Across Fence|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/10/09/446866267/in-a-first-border-agent-indicted-for-killing-mexican-teen-across-fence|website=[[NPR]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> Swartz was charged with [[second degree murder]] for the killing. He was acquitted on the murder charge and the jury failed to reach a verdict on lesser charges.\n\n==Incident==\nAround 11:30 p.m. on Wednesday, October 10, 2012, John Zu\u00f1iga, a police officer in [[Nogales, Arizona]],  received a call reporting \"suspicious activity\" on International Street, a road running directly along the  border. Getting to the scene, Zu\u00f1iga heard from another police officer from Nogales, Quinardo Garci, that  two men carrying \"bundles taped to their backs\" had climbed the fence into the United States. Identifying the bundles, on the basis of similar incidents in the past, as most probably containing [[marijuana]], they called out for back up.<ref name=shots/>\n\nAfter several [[United States Border Patrol|Border Patrol]] and [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|Customs]] agents arrived, they saw the two men scaling the fence back into Mexico, empty-handed and with nothing on their backs. They commanded the two men to climb back down. At that time, Garcia and Zu\u00f1iga stated in their reports that they saw \"rocks flying through the air\"<ref name=\"tucson.com\">{{cite news|title=Border agent's murder trial postponed|url=http://tucson.com/news/border-agent-s-murder-trial-postponed/article_561ac027-ef47-5d29-8d01-9c073669afff.html|date=2016-01-05|first=Perla |last=Trevizo|newspaper=Arizona Daily Star|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> at the assorted agents and also heard \"gunfire\", although they were unable to identify its source.<ref name=shots/><ref name=\"CarranzaTeen\"/> \n\nIn the days following the incident, the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] agency stated that\n:After verbal commands from agents to cease [assaulting the agents with rocks] were ignored, one agent then discharged his service firearm. One of the subjects appeared to have been hit.\n\nThe person hit was Jos\u00e9 Antonio Elena Rodr\u00edguez, a 16-year old resident of [[Nogales, Sonora|Nogales, Mexico]]. He was unarmed, standing on the Mexican side of the border on a sidewalk on Calle Internacional street, in front of a doctor's office, below a sign reading \"Medical Emergencies\" in Spanish. He was hit from behind by 10 bullets.<ref name=\"GUARDIAN1\"/> The [[autopsy]] revealed that gunshot wounds to the head, [[lung]]s, and [[artery|arteries]] killed him.<ref name=shots/><ref name=\"NPR1\"/>\n\n==Trial==\nU.S. Border Patrol agent Lonnie Ray Swartz was charged with [[second degree murder]] for the killing of Jos\u00e9 Rodr\u00edguez. There had been a number of similar incidents in the preceding decade, but this was the first time a US law enforcement officer was charged in relation to a killing that took part across the US\u2013Mexican border.<ref name=NPR1 /><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis|first=Charles|date=January 4, 2015|title=U.S. Customs and Border Protection Has Killed Nearly 50 People in 10 Years. Most Were Unarmed.|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120687/border-patrol-officers-get-impunity-anonymity-immigrant-killings|newspaper=[[The New Republic]]|access-date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the trial, which began in late 2015, the defendant said he had used deadly force because Rodriguez \"had been throwing rocks\".<ref name=shots/> A witness testified that Rodr\u00edguez was not throwing rocks at the law enforcement officers but prosecutors acknowledged that Rodr\u00edguez was throwing rocks across the border and went on to state that \"he did not deserve to die\" for this.<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\">{{cite news|title=Mistrial announced for U.S. border agent linked to teenager's fatal shooting|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mistrial-us-border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-manslaughter-charges-today-2018-04-23/|accessdate=May 24, 2018|publisher=CBS News|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> The U.S. Customs and Border Protection refused to release surveillance-camera footage of the incident.<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/>\n\nAfter the testimony of the director of the medical examiner in [[Miami-Dade County]], Florida, Emma Lew, who stated that Swartz's first shot \"likely hit the boy in the middle of his back as he was running,\" the prosecution rested its case in the trial on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/040518_swartz_trial/swartz-trial-defense-struggles-with-first-witness-after-prosecution-rests/|title=\nSwartz trial: Defense struggles with first witness after prosecution rests|first=Paul|last= Ingram|publisher=Tucson Sentinel|date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2018, Swartz was acquitted of the charge for second-degree murder; the jury was [[deadlock]]ed on lesser charges.<ref name=\"azcentral-notguilty-2018-04-23\">{{Cite news|last1=Carranza |first1=Rafael  |last2=O'Dell |first2=Rob |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/2018/04/23/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-found-not-guilty-cross-border-slaying-mexican-teen/544197002/|title=Border Patrol agent Lonnie Swartz found not guilty in cross-border slaying of Mexican teen|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=April 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n==Aftermath==\nThe judge presiding on the trial, [[Raner Collins]], declared a [[mistrial]]. The head of the Tucson union for Border Patrol officers, stated, after the jury's decision was announced, that \"justice was properly served\" and that the union was \"pretty happy with it\".<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/> \n\nAfter the jury's decision was reported, protesters gathered outside the federal courthouse in downtown Tucson late Monday afternoon, on 23  April,<ref name=blocked>{{cite news|date=16 April 2018|title=Protesters block I-10 on/off ramps for several hours|url=https://www.kold.com/story/37967210/border-patrol-shooting-lonnie-swarts-jose-elena-rodriguez/|work=[[KOLD-TV|Kold TV News]] |location=Tucson, Arizona|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and blocked off the intersection in front of it. Among those participating in the protest was the mother of Carlos LaMadrid, another Mexican teen who had been shot and killed by Border Patrol agents (in 2011).<ref name=retried>{{Cite news|last1=Carranza |first1=Rafael |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2018/05/11/border-patrol-agent-lonnie-swartz-retried-death-jose-antonio-elena-rodriguez/602687002/|title=Border Patrol agent will be retried in fatal cross-border shooting of teen|date=May 11, 2018|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=June 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n==Retrials==\nOn Friday 13 Decmber 2019, Assistant U.S. Attorney May Sue Feldmeier announced that prosecutors would seek a retrial on the two lesser charges<ref group=note>The lesser charges were for voluntary and involuntary manslaughter.</ref> against Swartz, who waived his right to appear in court. The case's presiding judge, U.S. District Judge Raner C. Collins, set the start of the new trial for 23 October 2020, with a motion hearing scheduled in July 2020.<ref name=retried/> \n\nIn 2919, the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] filed a suit in the federal district court in Tucson on behalf of the family of Jose Antonio Elena Rodriguez  against the border patrol agent who shot and killed him seeking  [[civil damages]]. In a preliminary hearing on Monday 9 December 2019, a video reconstruction of the shooting, including portions of video clips shot by two border cameras operated by the Border Patrol,<ref group=note>According to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' report, one camera  was mounted on a pole near the scene of the shooting, just west of the primary port of entry in Nogales, while the other was mounted about 2,500 feet away and east of the port of entry.</ref> was shown by the prosecution. Defense attorneys asked the judge not to permit the video reconstruction to be shown at the trial, arguing that \"the video evidence is unreliable.\"<ref name=video>{{cite news |last= O'Dell|first=Rob|date=14 December 2019 |title=Video of teen killed by Border Patrol agent shows he was facedown on ground when shots fired |url=https://eu.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/border-issues/2017/06/19/nogales-teen-elena-rodriguez-ground-when-shot-border-agent-lonnie-swartz/408088001/|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Review of similar incidents==\nA 2013 review by the Police Executive Research Forum (PERF) reviewed 67 shooting incidents that resulted in 19 people dying, during the period from January 2010 through October 2012. The review found agents guilty of criminal conduct in 3 of the incidents. Two agents faced disciplinary action in the form of an \"oral reprimand\".<ref name=\"FatalShootingCBS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of killings by law enforcement officers in the United States, October 2012]]\n*''[[Hernandez v. Mesa]]''\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}} \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*{{cite journal |last=The Police Executive Research Forum |first=|url=https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/documents/PERFReport.pdf|date=February 2013 |title=U.S. Customs and Border Protection Use of Force 