{"title_page": "Idukki district", "text_new": "{{About|Idukki |the Idukki town|Idukki, India}}\n{{other uses|Idukki (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Idukki District\n| native_name                     = \n| nickname                        = The land of spices in Kerala\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of districts of Kerala|District]] in [[Kerala]]\n| image_skyline                   = Sunrise at Munnar,Kerala.jpg\n| image_caption                   = A surise from [[Munnar]] in Idukki.\n| image_map                       = India Kerala Idukki district.svg\n| pushpin_map                     =\n| pushpin_label_position          = left\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|9.85|N|76.94|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Kerala]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = 1972\n| seat_type                       = Headquarters\n| seat                            = [[Painavu]]\n| leader_title1                   = Collector\n| leader_name1                    = Sri H Dineshan IAS\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 4358\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 1200\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 1,108,974\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_density_km2          = 254\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| demographics1_title2            = Spoken\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = 68XXXX\n| postal_code                     = \n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-KL]]\n| registration_plate              = {{ubl|KL-06 (Idukki)|KL-37 (Vandipperiyar)|KL-38 (Thodupuzha)|KL-68 (Devikulam)|KL-69 (Udumbanchola)|KLI (Old).}}\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.idukki.nic.in}}\n}}\n'''Idukki''' is a [[Districts of Kerala|district]] in the Indian state of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA8822F3923774E0440003BA962ED3|Idukki District (Variant \u2013 V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> It was constituted on 26 January 1972, by splitting the district of [[Kottayam District|Kottayam]] into two parts. Its division was earlier headquartered at [[Kottayam]] city, but moved to [[Painavu]] in June 1976. Idukki district lies amid the [[Western Ghats]] of Kerala. Though it is regarded as the second-largest district in the region, it has the lowest population density among the districts of Kerala,<ref>{{Citation|title=List of districts of Kerala|date=2020-03-08|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_districts_of_Kerala&oldid=944617285|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> the urban population being higher than the rural. Idukki is rich in forests and also known as the \"Spice Garden of Kerala\".\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name of the district is derived from the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam]] word ''idukku'' (\u0d07\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d), meaning narrow [[Canyon|gorge]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} \n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Kattappana.jpg|thumb|right|Kattappana]]\n\nIdukki has an area of {{convert|4358|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and is the second-largest district of Kerala (the largest being [[Palakkad District|Palakkad]]). Rugged mountains and forests cover about 97 percent of the total area of the district. The district consists of five taluks: [[Thodupuzha]], [[Devikulam]], [[Idukki]], [[Udumbanchola]], and [[Peerumedu]]. The district borders the Kerala districts of [[Pathanamthitta District|Pathanamthitta]] in the south, [[Kottayam District|Kottayam]] in the southwest, [[Ernakulam District|Ernakulam]] in the northwest, and [[Thrissur District|Thrissur]] in the north. Idukki also shares borders with [[Coimbatore District|Coimbatore]], [[Dindigul District|Dindigul]], small parts of [[Tenkasi district|Tenkasi]], [[Tiruppur District|Tiruppur]], [[Theni District|Theni]], and [[Virudhunagar district|Virudhunagar]] districts of [[Tamil Nadu]] in the east. Idukki is not connected to rail or air networks yet and is accessible only by road. National Highway NH 49 and State highways 13 and 33 pass through the district.<ref name=\"Idukki District\">{{cite web|url=http://idukki.nic.in/map.htm |title=Tourist Map of Idukki District |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217044751/http://idukki.nic.in/map.htm|archive-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Anamudi]] and [[Meesapulimala]], the two highest peaks in India south of the Himalayas, are located in Idukki district. Anamudi is situated in the Kuttampuzha Panchayat of Adimali Block in the [[Kannan Devan Hills]] village of Devikulam taluk. Thirteen other peaks in the district exceed a height of {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. [[Periyar River|Periyar]], Thodupuzhayar, Muthirappuzhayar, and Thalayar are the important rivers of the district.\n[[Idukki Dam]], [[Asia]]'s largest [[arch dam]], is located in the [[Idukki Township]]. The dam is located at the point where the Periyar flows through the gorge formed between two high and massive rocks known as 'Kuravan' and 'Kurathi'.<ref name=\"Idukki District\"/> The Idukki Hydroelectric Project caters to more than 60% of the power requirements of the state of [[Kerala]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=47,666|13=1911|14=99,564|15=1921|16=1,08,751|17=1931|18=1,87,680|19=1941|20=2,44,296|21=1951|22=3,31,422|23=1961|24=5,74,844|25=1971|26=7,58,166|27=1981|28=9,55,241|29=1991|30=10,55,023|31=2001|32=11,29,221|33=2011|34=11,08,974|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}According to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]], Idukki district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 1,108,974.<ref name=\"districtcensus\">{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 30 September 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> This places it at 416th among the 640 [[districts of India]]. The district has a population density of {{convert|254|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}}. Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001\u20132011 was \u22121.93% due to emigration and low fertility rates. Idukki has a [[sex ratio]] of 1,006 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1,000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 92.2 percent.<ref name=districtcensus/>\n\nMost of the people of Idukki speak [[Malayalam]]. The taluks of Devikulam, Udumbanchola, and Peermade have a significant population of [[Tamil language|Tamil]] speakers.<ref>http://www.theweekendleader.com/Causes/912/idukki-for-tn.html</ref><ref>https://zeenews.india.com/news/kerala/kerala-to-probe-campaign-to-hive-off-idukki-district_820970.html</ref>About 40 percent of the people in [[Munnar]] are Tamil speakers.<ref>https://zeenews.india.com/news/kerala/kerala-to-probe-campaign-to-hive-off-idukki-district_820970.html</ref>\n{{bar box\n| title    = Languages in Idukki District<ref name=\"Language\">{{cite web |title=Census of India - Language |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html |website= censusindia.gov.in |accessdate= 17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| titlebar = #FCD116\n| left1    = Language\n| right1   = Speakers\n| float    = right\n| bars     = \n{{bar percent|[[Malayalam]]|red|81.97}}\n{{bar percent|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|green|17.48}}\n{{bar percent|[[Kannada]]|orange|0.16}}\n{{bar percent|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]|yellow|0.13}}\n{{bar percent|Others|grey|0.26}}\n| caption = Distribution of languages<br>\n{{small|Source: 2011 Census}}\n}}\n===Technology===\nIdukki district was the first in [[India]] to get connected to a super-fast broad band system as a part of the [[Digital India]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hi-Speed Rural Broadband Network|url=http://businesswireindia.com/news/news-details/government-india-commissions-indias-first-hi-speed-rural-broadband-net/42188|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> It was also the first to get BSNL 4G in whole country, taking the number of 4G operators in the district to four, including [[Vodafone Idea Limited|Vodafone Idea Ltd]], [[Jio]], and [[Bharti Airtel]].\n\n==Religion==\n{{bar box\n| title    = Religions in Idukki District\n| titlebar = #Fcd116\n| left1    = Religion\n| right1   = Percent\n| float    = right\n| bars     = \n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|48.86}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|43.42}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|7.41}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|0.3}}\n| caption = Distribution of religions<br/>\n{{small|Source: 2011 Census.}}\n}}\n[[File:Thodupuzha_Sree_Krishna_Swami_Temple_DSC02584.JPG|thumb|[[Sree Krishna Swami Temple, Thodupuzha]]]]\nAccording to the 2011 census, [[Hindus]] make up 46.76% (541,854) of the population, with [[Christians]] at 45.92% (481,507) and [[Muslims]] at 7.32% (82,206).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/279-idukki.html|title=Idukki District Population Census 2011, Kerala literacy sex ratio and density|website=www.census2011.co.in|access-date=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tourist Spots==\n===Munnar===\n[[File:View of tea plantations from Munnar.jpg|thumb|Tea plantations in Munnar]]\n[[Munnar]] was the summer resort of the British Government in the south. The town is situated at the convergence of three mountain streams, namely [[Muthirapuzha River|Muthirappuzha]], Nallathanni, and Kundala. Munnar has some of the largest tea plantations in the world. This hill station, which is more than 5,000 feet above sea level, is a tourist attraction noted for its scenic landscapes.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Most of the native flora and fauna of Munnar have disappeared due to severe habitat fragmentation resultant from the creation of the plantations. However, some species continue to survive and thrive in several [[Protected areas of Kerala|protected areas]] nearby, including the new [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] to the east, the [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Manjampatti Valley]], and the Amaravati reserve forest of [[Indira Gandhi National Park|Indira Gandhi Wildlife Sanctuary]] to the northeast, the [[Eravikulam National Park]] and [[Anamudi Shola National Park]] in the north, and the [[Pampadum Shola National Park]] to the south. The [[Palani Hills National Park]] is proposed to come up to the east of Idukki. These protected areas are especially known for several [[threatened]] and [[Endemism|endemic]] species including the [[Nilgiri tahr]], the [[grizzled giant squirrel]], the [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], the [[Indian elephant|elephant]], the [[gaur]], the [[Nilgiri langur]], the [[Sambar (deer)|sambar]], and the [[neelakurinji]] (that blossoms only once in twelve years).<ref>{{cite news |title=Government of Kerala, Forest and Wildlife Department, Notification No. 36/2006 F&WLD |date=6 October 2006 |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://kurinji.in/sro.html |work=Kerala Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mathew |last=Roy |date=25 September 2006 |title=Proposal for Kurinjimala sanctuary awaits Cabinet nod |work=The Hindu |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/25/stories/2006092510910400.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe former Kunda Valley Railway in Munnar was destroyed by a flood in 1924, but tourism officials are considering reconstructing the railway line to attract tourists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/munnar-may-soon-get-train-service-nearly-a-century-after-the-great-flood-of-99-washed-away-kerala-s-first-railway-line-369776.html|title=Munnar May Soon Get Train Service, Nearly A Century After The 'Great Flood Of 99' Destroyed It|date=2019-06-24|website=indiatimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n===Vagamon===\n[[File:Vagamon meadows.JPG|thumb|right|Vagamon meadows, [[Kerala]], [[India]]]]\n[[File:Western Ghats as seen from Vagamon View Point.jpg|thumb|left|Western Ghats as seen from [[Vagamon]] View Point]]\n[[Vagamon]] is a hill station situated 1,200 meters above sea level, 37&nbsp;km from [[Pala, Kerala|Pala]] and 42&nbsp;km from [[Thodupuzha]].\n\nThis hill station provides options of trekking, para gliding or rock climbing for adventure-seekers, and has many varieties of flora and fauna. Evergreen trees, tall grasses, and shrubs are present in the lower regions of Vagamon. Many rare species of birds, insects, wild buffaloes, and elephants can be easily located in the forests. The main attractions here are mist-covered mountains and lakes, pilgrim centers (Kurishumala, Murugan temple, and burial chamber of a Sufi saint), and pine forests.\n\n===Ramakkalmedu===\n[[File:Statue of Kuruvan & Kuruthi.jpg|thumb|Statue of Kuruvan and Kuruthi in [[Ramakkalmedu]]]]\n[[File:View of Tamil Nadu, from Ramakkalmedu.jpg|thumb|View of Tamil Nadu from Ramakkalmedu]]\n[[Ramakkalmedu]] (\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d7d\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d1f\u0d4d\u200c) is a [[hill station]] and [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the Idukki district. It is located about 15&nbsp;km from [[Nedumkandam]] on the [[Munnar]]-[[Thekkady]] route.\n\nRamakalmedu stands tall in the Western Ghats at a height of 3,500 feet above sea level. The ecosystem of the area consists largely of Shola forest-grasslands, with sporadic bamboo forests.\n\nConstant wind is another factor that makes Ramakkalmedu unique. The wind blows at a speed around 35&nbsp;km/hour throughout the year, irrespective of the season and time. Tourist villages like Pushpakandam and Kuruvikanam near Ramakkalmedu are home to private wind energy farms, with a capacity of about 12.5 MW. This electricity is distributed to the Kerala State Electricity Board. Ramakkalmedu has the potential to produce more electricity, as it is said to be one of the most windy areas in Asia.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Thekkady===\n[[File:Periyar Wildlife Preserve.jpg|thumb|Misty Thekkady]]\n[[File:Cardamom Hills.jpg|thumb|Cardamom Hills]]\n[[Thekkady]] is located close to the Kerala-[[Tamil Nadu]] border, about {{convert|257|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Thiruvananthapuram|Trivandrum]], 140&nbsp;km from Madurai City and [[Madurai Airport]], 145&nbsp;km from [[Cochin International Airport]], and 114&nbsp;km from [[Kottayam]] railway station. The sanctuary at Thekkady is known for its dense [[evergreen]] and semi-evergreen, moist [[deciduous]] [[forest]]s and [[savanna]] grass lands. It is home to [[herd]]s of [[elephant]]s, [[sambar deer|sambar]], [[tiger]]s, [[gaur]], [[lion-tailed macaque]]s and [[Nilgiri langur]]s.\n\nThe [[Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary]] is spread across {{convert|777|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, of which {{convert|360|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} is thick evergreen forest. The wildlife sanctuary was declared a tiger reserve in 1978. The splendid artificial lake formed by the [[Mullaperiyar Dam]] across the [[Periyar River]] adds to the charm of the park. The greatest attractions of Periyar are the herds of wild elephants, deer, and bison that come down to drink in the lake. The sanctuary can be accessed through a trekking route, boating, or jeep safari.<ref name=\"Tourist Guide to Kerala\">Tourist Guide to Kerala By Motilal (UK) Books of India, Various, V. Subburaj</ref> Thekkady is considered a haven for natural [[spice]]s such as [[black pepper]], [[cardamom]], [[cinnamon]], [[nutmeg]], nutmace, [[ginger]], and [[clove]].\n[[File:Periyar National Park 02.jpg|thumb|left|Submerged trees in Periyar National Park]]\n\n===Marayur===\n[[File:Sandalforest.jpg|thumb|left|Walkway through the [[sandalwood]] forest]]\n[[Marayur]] is a remote village on the eastern slopes of the Western Ghats. Relics of the New Stone Age have been unearthed here. It has ancient stone cabins, called 'Muniyaras', and is the only place in Kerala with natural growth of [[sandalwood]] trees. Marayur has more than 1,000 species of flowering plants and is a well-known repository of medicinal plants. There are 114 endemic species and the sighting of ''[[Albizia]] lathamii'', a critically endangered tree, was recently reported from the dry forests. Chinnar \u2013 the wildlife sanctuary in Marayur \u2013 has recorded the largest number of [[reptile|reptilian]] species, including the mugger crocodile, in Kerala. With 225 recorded species of birds, it is one of the richest areas in avian diversity in South India. The forests in Marayur preserve a population of the endangered grizzled giant squirrel. The rare white bison has been recently reported in Chinnar wildlife sanctuary. Other important mammals found are elephant, tiger, leopard, gaur, sambar, spotted deer, Nilgiri ''thar'', common langur, bonnet macaque, etc. The phenomenon of butterfly migration occurs in between the monsoons.\n\nMaryoor has got a number of sandalwood forests. Processing of sandalwood and its associated oil forms part of the local economy and a depot near Marayur town is supporting this industry. Sandal wood or ''[[Santalum album]]'' is a parasitic tree having a fragrant and close-grained yellowish heartwood. Sandalwood oil, also known as \u2018liquid gold,\u2019 is extracted from the roots and wood of sandalwood. This oil is a costly item marketed at a few choosy outlets all over the state. A climate with low rainfall is suitable for the growth of choice sandalwood trees from which good quality oil can be extracted. The 93&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> Marayur reserve forest is believed to have about sixty thousand naturally grown sandalwood trees, of which nearly 2,000 trees had been allegedly plundered in just one year since January 2004, when the last survey was conducted. The auction-rate for first quality Marayur sandal is quoted at [[Rs.]]1100 per kg, according to forest department sources (2004).\n\n==Wildlife sanctuaries==\n\n===Idukki Wildlife Sanctuary===\nIdukki Wildlife Sanctuary came into existence in 1976. It is located in the Thodupuzha and Udumbanchola taluks in Idukki\ndistrict. It has an area of 105.364sq.km. The altitude ranges from 450 to 1272 m. The highest peak is Vanjur Medu (1272m).\n\nThe major rivers flowing through the area are the [[Periyar (river)|Periyar]] and the Cheruthoniar.<ref>http://www.forest.kerala.gov.in/index.php/wildlife/2015-03-16-09-50-24/2015-06-26-09-04-29/idukki-wildlife-sanctuary</ref>\n\n===Eravikulam Wild Life Sanctuary===\n[[File:Nilgiri Tahr Adult.jpg|thumb|250px|Nilagiri Tahr]]\n[[Eravikulam National Park|Eravikulam]] is another wildlife sanctuary proclaimed as a National Park. It supports the largest population of [[Nilgiri tahr]] in the world. Anamudi peak is on the southern part of this park.\nMost of the park is grassland and the average altitude is more than 5000 feet above [[Mean sea level|sea level]]. Heavy rain and gushing winds makes the area inaccessible during the monsoon season. The famous Neelakurinji ([[Strobilanthes kunthiana]]) grows here. It has a flowering cycle of 12 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/idukki.htm|title=Information and Public Relations Department, Govt. of Kerala|access-date=13 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228064818/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/idukki.htm|archive-date=28 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Twenty six species of [[mammals]] have been recorded in the park including the largest surviving population of [[Nilgiri tahr]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Munnar|url=http://www.keralatourism.org/destination/destination.php?id=306|access-date=22 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118183559/http://www.keralatourism.org/destination/destination.php?id=306|archive-date=18 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> estimated at about 750 individuals. The other [[ungulates]] are [[gaur]], [[Indian muntjac]] and [[sambar deer]]. [[Golden jackal]], [[jungle cat]], [[Dhole|wild dog]], [[dhole]], [[leopard]] and tiger are the main predators.  Some little-known animals such as [[Nilgiri langur]], [[stripe-necked mongoose]], [[Indian porcupine]], [[Nilgiri marten]], [[Oriental small-clawed otter|small clawed otter]], [[ruddy mongoose]], and [[Funambulus sublineatus|dusky palm squirrel]] are also found.<ref>UNEP (05/07/2007) World Commission on Protected Areas, World Database on Protected Areas, Eravikulam National Park, Retrieved 7 May 2007 {{cite web |url=http://sea.unep-wcmc.org/wdpa/sitedetails.cfm?siteid=700&level=nat |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929140736/http://sea.unep-wcmc.org/wdpa/sitedetails.cfm?siteid=700&level=nat |archive-date=29 September 2007  }}</ref> [[Indian elephant|Elephants]] make seasonal visits.\n\n132 species of birds have been recorded which include endemics like [[black-and-orange flycatcher]], [[Nilgiri pipit]], [[Nilgiri wood pigeon]], [[Brachypteryx major|white bellied shortwing]], [[Eumyias albicaudata|Nilgiri flycatcher]] and Kerala [[laughingthrush]].\n\nEndemic butterflies confined to the shola-grass land ecosystem like the [[Mycalesis oculus|red disk bushbrown]] and Palni four-wing are among the 101 species in the park.\n\n===Periyar Tiger Reserve===\n[[Periyar National Park|Periyar Tiger Reserve]], Thekkady, is sprawled over an area of 925&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. Periyar is one of the 50 tiger reserves in India. This zealously guarded and efficiently managed reserve is a repository of rare, endemic and endangered flora and fauna, and forms the major watershed of two important rivers of Kerala, the Periyar, and Pamba.\n[[File:Wild elephants, Munnar.jpg|thumb|Wild elephants in [[Munnar]], Kerala]]\n'''Periyar National Park and Wildlife Sanctuary''' (PNP) is a [[protected area]] in the districts of Idukki and Pathanamthitta in Kerala. It is notable as an [[Project Elephant|elephant reserve]] and a [[Project Tiger|tiger reserve]]. The protected area covers an area of {{convert|925|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}. {{convert|305|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} of the core zone was declared as the Periyar National Park in 1982\n\n===Pampadumshola National Park===\n[[Pampadum Shola National Park]] is the smallest [[National parks of India|national park]] in [[Kerala]] state, [[South India]].<ref name=\"envis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kerenvis.nic.in/isbeid/forest.htm |last=Envis Kerala |year=2009 |title=Forest |publisher=Kerala State Council for Science, Technology and Environment |access-date=18 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311001130/http://www.kerenvis.nic.in/isbeid/forest.htm |archive-date=11 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>Online Highways LLC. (2004) India | Kerala | Devikulam\nPambadum Shola National Park, Retrieved 6 April 2007 [http://www.india9.com/i9show/Pambadum-Shola-National-Park-57785.htm]</ref> The park is administered by the Kerala Department of Forests and Wildlife, Munnar Wildlife Division, together with the nearby [[Mathikettan Shola National Park]], [[Eravikulam National Park]], [[Anamudi Shola National Park]], [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]] and the [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]].<ref>K.S. Sudhi (3 November 2006) The Hindu, retrieved 21 June 2007 [http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/03/stories/2006110300820200.htm ''New lives bloom in Rajamala'']</ref> The park adjoins the Allinagaram Reserved Forest within the proposed [[Palani Hills Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]]. The Western Ghats, Anamalai Sub-Cluster, including these parks, is under consideration by the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site#World Heritage Committee Session|World Heritage Committee]] for selection as a [[World Heritage Site]].<ref name=\"UNESCO\" >UNESCO, World Heritage sites, Tentative lists, Western Ghats sub cluster, Niligiris. retrieved 20 April 2007 [https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2103/ World Heritage sites, Tentative lists]</ref>\n\n===Kurinjimala Sanctuary===\n[[File:Strobilanths kunthiana.jpg|thumb|[[Neelakurinji]]]]\n[[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] protects the approximately 32&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> core habitat of the endangered [[Neelakurinji]] plant in [[Kottakamboor]] and [[Vattavada]] villages in [[Devikulam]] Taluk, Idukki district of [[Kerala]] State in [[South India]].<ref>[http://kurinji.in/kurinjimap.html map]</ref>\n\n===Protected areas===\n[[File:GrizzledSquirell-cauvery wls.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Giant grizzled squirrel]]\nThis district has several [[Protected areas of Kerala|protected areas]] including: [[Periyar Tiger Reserve]] in the south, [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] to the east, [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]] to the northeast, [[Eravikulam National Park]] and [[Anamudi Shola National Park]] to the north and [[Pampadum Shola National Park]] to the south.  These protected areas are well known for several [[threatened]] and [[Endemism|endemic]] species including [[Bengal tiger|tiger]], [[Nilgiri tahr]], [[grizzled giant squirrel]], [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], [[Indian elephant|elephant]], gaur, sambar deer, [[purple frog]] and [[neelakurinji]].<ref>Government of Kerala, Forest and Wildlife Department, Notification No. 36/2006 F&WLD (6 October 2006) Retrieved 5 December 2007 [http://kurinji.in/sro.html Kerala Gazette]</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mathew |last=Roy |date=25 September 2006 |title=Proposal for Kurinjimala sanctuary awaits Cabinet nod |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/25/stories/2006092510910400.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Waterfalls==\nThere are several waterfalls in Idukki, most of them are active only during the monsoon season.\n\n===Cheeyappara===\nThe [[Cheeyappara Waterfalls]]('''\u0d1a\u0d40\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d31''') is on the [[Kochi, India|Kochi]] \u2013 [[Madurai]] Highway in Idukki district ([[National Highway 49 (India)|National Highway 49]]), between [[Neriamangalam]] and [[Adimali]]. The Cheeyappara Waterfall cascades down in seven steps. This place is well known for trekking.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===Thommankuthu===\n[[File:Thommankuthu waterfalls.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thommankuthu Waterfalls]]\n'''[[Thommankuthu]] (\u0d24\u0d4a\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d7b\u0d15\u0d41\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d4d)''' is a scenic waterfall near [[Thodupuzha]] in the district. Thomankoothu waterfalls is not a single waterfall but a series of 12 falls over a distance of 5km.<ref>http://www.forest.kerala.gov.in/index.php/idukki/thommankuthu-eco-tourism</ref> It is one of the major eco-tourism centers in Idukki, Kerala.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n{{Main|Administration of Idukki district}}\n[[File:Thodupuzha Civil Station.jpg|thumb|right|Thodupuzha Civil Station]]\nIdukki District is divided into eight community development blocks (block panchayats).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory: Block Panchayats of Idukki, Kerala |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj, Government of India|url=}}</ref> The community development blocks are further divided into [[taluka]]s. The blocks are:<ref>{{Cite web|title=Idukki Zilla Panchayat|url=http://idukki.nic.in/local.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209003839/http://www.idukki.nic.in/local.htm |archive-date=9 December 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* Adimaly Block \n* Azhutha Block \n* Devikulam Block\n* Elamdesom Block \n* Idukki Block \n* Kattappana Block \n* Nedumkandam Block\n* Thodupuzha Block \n}}\n\n===Municipalities===\n* [[Thodupuzha]]\n* [[Kattappana]]\n\n===Towns===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Thodupuzha|Thodupuzha (TDPA)]]\n* [[Kattappana|Kattappana (KTPNA)]]\n* [[Adimali]]\n* [[Munnar|Munnar (MNR)]]\n* [[Devikulam]]\n* [[Chinnakanal]]\n* [[Rajakkad]]\n* [[Rajakumari, Idukki district|Rajakumari]]\n* [[Udumbanchola]]\n* [[Nedumkandam|Nedumkandam (NDKM)]]\n* [[Anakkara (Idukki)|Anakkara]]\n* [[Idukki township|Idukki]]\n** [[Cheruthoni]]\n** [[Mannathara]]\n** Mariyapuram\n** Keerithode\n** Kanjikuzhy\n** [[Murickassery]]\n* [[Thopramkudy]]\n* [[Moolamattom|Moolamattom (MLTM)]]\n** [[Muttom, Thodupuzha|Muttom]]\n* [[Karimannoor]]\n*[[Vannappuram]]\n* [[Peruvanthanam]]\n* [[Peerumedu]]\n** [[Kuttikkanam]]\n* [[Upputhara]]\n* [[Elappara]]\n* [[Wagamon]]\n* [[Vandiperiyar]]\n* [[Kumily|Kumily (KMLY)]]\n** [[Thekkady]]\n\n}}\n\n===Borders===\n* Cumbummettu\n* [[Kumily]]\n\n==Culture==\nCulture in Idukki is mixed since it constitutes of migrated people from other parts of [[Kerala]] and native tribals. The presence of a large number of tribal populations is peculiar to Idukki District. [[Kozhimala|Kovilmala]], near Kattappana in Idukki is home to one of the still ruling tribal kings in India, Kovilmala Raja Mannan.[[Kozhimala|Kovilmala]] is the headquarters of Mannan community who preserves certain customs, traditions, and form of governance, making them a unique tribal unit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/young-tribal-king-dies-of-heart-attack/article2756552.ece|title=Young tribal king dies of heart attack|last=Correspondent|first=A|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> The system of governance here is a [[Democracy|democratic]] - [[monarchy]] in which a king is elected by the people to rule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alienadv.com/activityDetails/3561/A-Day-with-Mannans-of-Kovilamala-Kingdom-Kerala/|title=A Day with Mannans of Kovilamala Kingdom Kerala|newspaper=www.alienadv.com|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIndigenous art forms in Idukki are not as popular as other major art forms. Tourist areas like [[Munnar]] and Thekkady welcome people by hosting popular art forms like [[Kathakali]].\n\n==Dams in Idukki==\n{{See also|SNC-Lavalin Kerala hydroelectric scandal}}\n[[File:Idukki arch Dam view 155706.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Idukki arch Dam]]\nThe first and oldest dam in Kerala is [[Mullaperiyar]]. It was inaugurated in 1895. The largest dam in Kerala is [[Idukki Dam]].It was built in 1955.\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Idukki Dam|Idukki Arch-Dam]]\n*[[Cheruthoni Dam|Cheruthoni]]\n*[[Mullaperiyar Dam|Mullapperiyar]]\n*[[Ponmudi Dam|Ponmudy]]\n*Kallarkutty Dam\n*Kundala Dam\n* Mattuppetti\n*Aanayirangal Dam\n*[[Bhoothathankettu]]\n*Sengulam Dam\n*Lower Periyar Dam\n*[[Malankara Dam|Malankara]]\n*Kallar Dam (Nedumkandam)\n*[[Kulamavu Dam|Kulamavu]]\n*Munnar Head Works\n*Erattayar Dam\n*Uluppuni Dam\n*Kochu Pamba\n}}\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\nThe roads in Idukki are part of Ghat roads. The major roads connect the city of [[Kochi]] to Tamil Nadu. The KK road (Kumili-Kottayam), the PT road (Puliyanmala-Thodupuzha State Highway-33) are some of the other busy roads.\n\n====Neriamangalam Bridge====\nThe [[Neriamangalam]] Bridge, built across the Periyar river, is often referred to as 'The Gateway to the Highranges' as it is on the way to the higher regions of Idukki district, especially Munnar. The bridge was made by the [[List of Maharajas of Travancore|Maharaja of Travancore]] in 1935.\n[[File:Neriamangalam bridge.PNG|thumb|right|Neryamangalam bridge]]\n\n===Rail===\nAt present, there is no railway in and to Idukki district of Kerala. The nearest railway stations are Kottayam (station code \u2013 KTYM), Aluva (Alwaye, station code \u2013 AWY), Ernakulam South (Ernakulam Jn., station code \u2013 ERS) and Ernakulam North (Ernakulam Town, station code \u2013 ERN).\n\n===Air===\nThe nearest airport to Idukki is [[Cochin International Airport]] and [[Coimbatore Airport]]. [[Airport Authority of India]]'s plan to set up an airport in Anakkara is in a conflict of environmental issues. Anakkara Airport will be a great leap in Idukki's complete development. The government claims this project will improve the tourism in the area. However, with Anakkara being situated in environmentally sensitive [[Western Ghats]], environmentalists and villagers argue that this can significantly impact the area's climatic conditions and livelihood of people. Also, the land identified for the project is one of the very few remaining paddy fields of the district, currently cultivating some of the rare indigenous varieties of rice which increases the concern about the project. Those opposing the airport also cite the economic benefits as Munnar, one of the key target destinations for the airport lies at about 100&nbsp;km from Anakkara and the time taken to reach there from [[Cochin International Airport]] is less than the time taken to reach from Anakkara.  Though there are no clear references online from the government on the objectives, benefits, and purpose of the proposed airport, anti-Anakkara-airport groups have set up social networking campaign sites explaining reasons why they claim the airport project should not be implemented.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Trissur district]]\n*[[Civil Station, Idukki]]\n*[[Keezhanthoor]]\n*[[Santhanpara]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Idukki district}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130724132707/http://www.idukki.nic.in/ Official Idukki District website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080531154944/http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1813/18130780.htm Human Development Index (HDI) and Gender Development Index (GDI)]\n* {{curlie|Regional/Asia/India/Kerala/Districts/Idukki/}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Idukki district\n| North     = [[Coimbatore district]], Tamil Nadu\n| Northeast = {{ubl|[[Coimbatore district]], Tamil Nadu| [[Tiruppur district]], Tamil Nadu | [[Dindigul district]], Tamil Nadu}}\n| East      = [[Theni district]], Tamil Nadu\n| Southeast = {{ubl|[[Virudhunagar district]], Tamil Nadu | [[Tirunelveli district]], Tamil Nadu}}\n| South     = [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n| Southwest =\n| West      = [[Kottayam district]]\n| Northwest = [[Ernakulam district]]\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles Related to Idukki\n| list  =\n{{Kerala}}\n{{Northern Travancore}}\n{{Idukki district}}\n{{Hindu temples in Kerala}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idukki}}\n[[Category:Districts of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Idukki district| ]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Idukki |the Idukki town|Idukki, India}}\n{{other uses|Idukki (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Idukki District\n| native_name                     = \n| nickname                        = The land of spices in Kerala\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of districts of Kerala|District]] in [[Kerala]]\n| image_skyline                   = Sunrise at Munnar,Kerala.jpg\n| image_caption                   = A surise from [[Munnar]] in Idukki.\n| image_map                       = India Kerala Idukki district.svg\n| pushpin_map                     =\n| pushpin_label_position          = left\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|9.85|N|76.94|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Kerala]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = 1972\n| seat_type                       = Headquarters\n| seat                            = [[Painavu]]\n| leader_title1                   = Collector\n| leader_name1                    = Sri H Dineshan IAS\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 4358\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 1200\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 1,108,974\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_density_km2          = 254\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| demographics1_title2            = Spoken\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = 68XXXX\n| postal_code                     = \n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-KL]]\n| registration_plate              = {{ubl|KL-06 (Idukki)|KL-37 (Vandipperiyar)|KL-38 (Thodupuzha)|KL-68 (Devikulam)|KL-69 (Udumbanchola)|KLI (Old).}}\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.idukki.nic.in}}\n}}\n'''Idukki''' is a [[Districts of Kerala|district]] in the Indian state of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA8822F3923774E0440003BA962ED3|Idukki District (Variant \u2013 V)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> It was constituted on 26 January 1972, by splitting the district of [[Kottayam District|Kottayam]] into two parts. Its division was earlier headquartered at [[Kottayam]] city, but moved to [[Painavu]] in June 1976. Idukki district lies amid the [[Western Ghats]] of Kerala. Though it is regarded as the second-largest district in the region, it has the lowest population density among the districts of Kerala,<ref>{{Citation|title=List of districts of Kerala|date=2020-03-08|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_districts_of_Kerala&oldid=944617285|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> the urban population being higher than the rural. Idukki is rich in forests and also known as the \"Spice Garden of Kerala\".\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name of the district is derived from the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam]] word ''idukku'' (\u0d07\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d), meaning narrow [[Canyon|gorge]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} \n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Kattappana.jpg|thumb|right|Kattappana]]\n\nIdukki has an area of {{convert|4358|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and is the second-largest district of Kerala (the largest being [[Palakkad District|Palakkad]]). Rugged mountains and forests cover about 97 percent of the total area of the district. The district consists of five taluks: [[Thodupuzha]], [[Devikulam]], [[Idukki]], [[Udumbanchola]], and [[Peerumedu]]. The district borders the Kerala districts of [[Pathanamthitta District|Pathanamthitta]] in the south, [[Kottayam District|Kottayam]] in the southwest, [[Ernakulam District|Ernakulam]] in the northwest, and [[Thrissur District|Thrissur]] in the north. Idukki also shares borders with [[Coimbatore District|Coimbatore]], [[Dindigul District|Dindigul]], small parts of [[Tenkasi district|Tenkasi]], [[Tiruppur District|Tiruppur]], [[Theni District|Theni]], and [[Virudhunagar district|Virudhunagar]] districts of [[Tamil Nadu]] in the east. Idukki is not connected to rail or air networks yet and is accessible only by road. National Highway NH 49 and State highways 13 and 33 pass through the district.<ref name=\"Idukki District\">{{cite web|url=http://idukki.nic.in/map.htm |title=Tourist Map of Idukki District |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217044751/http://idukki.nic.in/map.htm|archive-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Anamudi]] and [[Meesapulimala]], the two highest peaks in India south of the Himalayas, are located in Idukki district. Anamudi is situated in the Kuttampuzha Panchayat of Adimali Block in the [[Kannan Devan Hills]] village of Devikulam taluk. Thirteen other peaks in the district exceed a height of {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. [[Periyar River|Periyar]], Thodupuzhayar, Muthirappuzhayar, and Thalayar are the important rivers of the district.\n[[Idukki Dam]], [[Asia]]'s largest [[arch dam]], is located in the [[Idukki Township]]. The dam is located at the point where the Periyar flows through the gorge formed between two high and massive rocks known as 'Kuravan' and 'Kurathi'.<ref name=\"Idukki District\"/> The Idukki Hydroelectric Project caters to more than 60% of the power requirements of the state of [[Kerala]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=47,666|13=1911|14=99,564|15=1921|16=1,08,751|17=1931|18=1,87,680|19=1941|20=2,44,296|21=1951|22=3,31,422|23=1961|24=5,74,844|25=1971|26=7,58,166|27=1981|28=9,55,241|29=1991|30=10,55,023|31=2001|32=11,29,221|33=2011|34=11,08,974|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}According to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]], Idukki district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 1,108,974.<ref name=\"districtcensus\">{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 30 September 2011 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> This places it at 416th among the 640 [[districts of India]]. The district has a population density of {{convert|254|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}}. Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001\u20132011 was \u22121.93% due to emigration and low fertility rates. Idukki has a [[sex ratio]] of 1,006 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1,000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 92.2 percent.<ref name=districtcensus/>\n\nMost of the people of Idukki speak [[Malayalam]]. The taluks of Devikulam, Udumbanchola, and Peermade have a significant population of [[Tamil language|Tamil]] speakers.<ref>http://www.theweekendleader.com/Causes/912/idukki-for-tn.html</ref><ref>https://zeenews.india.com/news/kerala/kerala-to-probe-campaign-to-hive-off-idukki-district_820970.html</ref>About 40 percent of the people in [[Munnar]] are Tamil speakers.<ref>https://zeenews.india.com/news/kerala/kerala-to-probe-campaign-to-hive-off-idukki-district_820970.html</ref>\n{{bar box\n| title    = Languages in Idukki District<ref name=\"Language\">{{cite web |title=Census of India - Language |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html |website= censusindia.gov.in |accessdate= 17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| titlebar = #FCD116\n| left1    = Language\n| right1   = Speakers\n| float    = right\n| bars     = \n{{bar percent|[[Malayalam]]|red|81.97}}\n{{bar percent|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|green|17.48}}\n{{bar percent|[[Kannada]]|orange|0.16}}\n{{bar percent|[[Telugu]]|yellow|0.13}}\n{{bar percent|Others|grey|0.26}}\n| caption = Distribution of languages<br>\n{{small|Source: 2011 Census}}\n}}\n===Technology===\nIdukki district was the first in [[India]] to get connected to a super-fast broad band system as a part of the [[Digital India]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hi-Speed Rural Broadband Network|url=http://businesswireindia.com/news/news-details/government-india-commissions-indias-first-hi-speed-rural-broadband-net/42188|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> It was also the first to get BSNL 4G in whole country, taking the number of 4G operators in the district to four, including [[Vodafone Idea Limited|Vodafone Idea Ltd]], [[Jio]], and [[Bharti Airtel]].\n\n==Religion==\n{{bar box\n| title    = Religions in Idukki District\n| titlebar = #Fcd116\n| left1    = Religion\n| right1   = Percent\n| float    = right\n| bars     = \n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|48.86}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|43.42}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|7.41}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|0.3}}\n| caption = Distribution of religions<br/>\n{{small|Source: 2011 Census.}}\n}}\n[[File:Thodupuzha_Sree_Krishna_Swami_Temple_DSC02584.JPG|thumb|[[Sree Krishna Swami Temple, Thodupuzha]]]]\nAccording to the 2011 census, [[Hindus]] make up 46.76% (541,854) of the population, with [[Christians]] at 45.92% (481,507) and [[Muslims]] at 7.32% (82,206).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/279-idukki.html|title=Idukki District Population Census 2011, Kerala literacy sex ratio and density|website=www.census2011.co.in|access-date=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tourist Spots==\n===Munnar===\n[[File:View of tea plantations from Munnar.jpg|thumb|Tea plantations in Munnar]]\n[[Munnar]] was the summer resort of the British Government in the south. The town is situated at the convergence of three mountain streams, namely [[Muthirapuzha River|Muthirappuzha]], Nallathanni, and Kundala. Munnar has some of the largest tea plantations in the world. This hill station, which is more than 5,000 feet above sea level, is a tourist attraction noted for its scenic landscapes.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Most of the native flora and fauna of Munnar have disappeared due to severe habitat fragmentation resultant from the creation of the plantations. However, some species continue to survive and thrive in several [[Protected areas of Kerala|protected areas]] nearby, including the new [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] to the east, the [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Manjampatti Valley]], and the Amaravati reserve forest of [[Indira Gandhi National Park|Indira Gandhi Wildlife Sanctuary]] to the northeast, the [[Eravikulam National Park]] and [[Anamudi Shola National Park]] in the north, and the [[Pampadum Shola National Park]] to the south. The [[Palani Hills National Park]] is proposed to come up to the east of Idukki. These protected areas are especially known for several [[threatened]] and [[Endemism|endemic]] species including the [[Nilgiri tahr]], the [[grizzled giant squirrel]], the [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], the [[Indian elephant|elephant]], the [[gaur]], the [[Nilgiri langur]], the [[Sambar (deer)|sambar]], and the [[neelakurinji]] (that blossoms only once in twelve years).<ref>{{cite news |title=Government of Kerala, Forest and Wildlife Department, Notification No. 36/2006 F&WLD |date=6 October 2006 |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://kurinji.in/sro.html |work=Kerala Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mathew |last=Roy |date=25 September 2006 |title=Proposal for Kurinjimala sanctuary awaits Cabinet nod |work=The Hindu |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/25/stories/2006092510910400.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe former Kunda Valley Railway in Munnar was destroyed by a flood in 1924, but tourism officials are considering reconstructing the railway line to attract tourists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/munnar-may-soon-get-train-service-nearly-a-century-after-the-great-flood-of-99-washed-away-kerala-s-first-railway-line-369776.html|title=Munnar May Soon Get Train Service, Nearly A Century After The 'Great Flood Of 99' Destroyed It|date=2019-06-24|website=indiatimes.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n\n===Vagamon===\n[[File:Vagamon meadows.JPG|thumb|right|Vagamon meadows, [[Kerala]], [[India]]]]\n[[File:Western Ghats as seen from Vagamon View Point.jpg|thumb|left|Western Ghats as seen from [[Vagamon]] View Point]]\n[[Vagamon]] is a hill station situated 1,200 meters above sea level, 37&nbsp;km from [[Pala, Kerala|Pala]] and 42&nbsp;km from [[Thodupuzha]].\n\nThis hill station provides options of trekking, para gliding or rock climbing for adventure-seekers, and has many varieties of flora and fauna. Evergreen trees, tall grasses, and shrubs are present in the lower regions of Vagamon. Many rare species of birds, insects, wild buffaloes, and elephants can be easily located in the forests. The main attractions here are mist-covered mountains and lakes, pilgrim centers (Kurishumala, Murugan temple, and burial chamber of a Sufi saint), and pine forests.\n\n===Ramakkalmedu===\n[[File:Statue of Kuruvan & Kuruthi.jpg|thumb|Statue of Kuruvan and Kuruthi in [[Ramakkalmedu]]]]\n[[File:View of Tamil Nadu, from Ramakkalmedu.jpg|thumb|View of Tamil Nadu from Ramakkalmedu]]\n[[Ramakkalmedu]] (\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d7d\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d1f\u0d4d\u200c) is a [[hill station]] and [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the Idukki district. It is located about 15&nbsp;km from [[Nedumkandam]] on the [[Munnar]]-[[Thekkady]] route.\n\nRamakalmedu stands tall in the Western Ghats at a height of 3,500 feet above sea level. The ecosystem of the area consists largely of Shola forest-grasslands, with sporadic bamboo forests.\n\nConstant wind is another factor that makes Ramakkalmedu unique. The wind blows at a speed around 35&nbsp;km/hour throughout the year, irrespective of the season and time. Tourist villages like Pushpakandam and Kuruvikanam near Ramakkalmedu are home to private wind energy farms, with a capacity of about 12.5 MW. This electricity is distributed to the Kerala State Electricity Board. Ramakkalmedu has the potential to produce more electricity, as it is said to be one of the most windy areas in Asia.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Thekkady===\n[[File:Periyar Wildlife Preserve.jpg|thumb|Misty Thekkady]]\n[[File:Cardamom Hills.jpg|thumb|Cardamom Hills]]\n[[Thekkady]] is located close to the Kerala-[[Tamil Nadu]] border, about {{convert|257|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Thiruvananthapuram|Trivandrum]], 140&nbsp;km from Madurai City and [[Madurai Airport]], 145&nbsp;km from [[Cochin International Airport]], and 114&nbsp;km from [[Kottayam]] railway station. The sanctuary at Thekkady is known for its dense [[evergreen]] and semi-evergreen, moist [[deciduous]] [[forest]]s and [[savanna]] grass lands. It is home to [[herd]]s of [[elephant]]s, [[sambar deer|sambar]], [[tiger]]s, [[gaur]], [[lion-tailed macaque]]s and [[Nilgiri langur]]s.\n\nThe [[Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary]] is spread across {{convert|777|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, of which {{convert|360|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} is thick evergreen forest. The wildlife sanctuary was declared a tiger reserve in 1978. The splendid artificial lake formed by the [[Mullaperiyar Dam]] across the [[Periyar River]] adds to the charm of the park. The greatest attractions of Periyar are the herds of wild elephants, deer, and bison that come down to drink in the lake. The sanctuary can be accessed through a trekking route, boating, or jeep safari.<ref name=\"Tourist Guide to Kerala\">Tourist Guide to Kerala By Motilal (UK) Books of India, Various, V. Subburaj</ref> Thekkady is considered a haven for natural [[spice]]s such as [[black pepper]], [[cardamom]], [[cinnamon]], [[nutmeg]], nutmace, [[ginger]], and [[clove]].\n[[File:Periyar National Park 02.jpg|thumb|left|Submerged trees in Periyar National Park]]\n\n===Marayur===\n[[File:Sandalforest.jpg|thumb|left|Walkway through the [[sandalwood]] forest]]\n[[Marayur]] is a remote village on the eastern slopes of the Western Ghats. Relics of the New Stone Age have been unearthed here. It has ancient stone cabins, called 'Muniyaras', and is the only place in Kerala with natural growth of [[sandalwood]] trees. Marayur has more than 1,000 species of flowering plants and is a well-known repository of medicinal plants. There are 114 endemic species and the sighting of ''[[Albizia]] lathamii'', a critically endangered tree, was recently reported from the dry forests. Chinnar \u2013 the wildlife sanctuary in Marayur \u2013 has recorded the largest number of [[reptile|reptilian]] species, including the mugger crocodile, in Kerala. With 225 recorded species of birds, it is one of the richest areas in avian diversity in South India. The forests in Marayur preserve a population of the endangered grizzled giant squirrel. The rare white bison has been recently reported in Chinnar wildlife sanctuary. Other important mammals found are elephant, tiger, leopard, gaur, sambar, spotted deer, Nilgiri ''thar'', common langur, bonnet macaque, etc. The phenomenon of butterfly migration occurs in between the monsoons.\n\nMaryoor has got a number of sandalwood forests. Processing of sandalwood and its associated oil forms part of the local economy and a depot near Marayur town is supporting this industry. Sandal wood or ''[[Santalum album]]'' is a parasitic tree having a fragrant and close-grained yellowish heartwood. Sandalwood oil, also known as \u2018liquid gold,\u2019 is extracted from the roots and wood of sandalwood. This oil is a costly item marketed at a few choosy outlets all over the state. A climate with low rainfall is suitable for the growth of choice sandalwood trees from which good quality oil can be extracted. The 93&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> Marayur reserve forest is believed to have about sixty thousand naturally grown sandalwood trees, of which nearly 2,000 trees had been allegedly plundered in just one year since January 2004, when the last survey was conducted. The auction-rate for first quality Marayur sandal is quoted at [[Rs.]]1100 per kg, according to forest department sources (2004).\n\n==Wildlife sanctuaries==\n\n===Idukki Wildlife Sanctuary===\nIdukki Wildlife Sanctuary came into existence in 1976. It is located in the Thodupuzha and Udumbanchola taluks in Idukki\ndistrict. It has an area of 105.364sq.km. The altitude ranges from 450 to 1272 m. The highest peak is Vanjur Medu (1272m).\n\nThe major rivers flowing through the area are the [[Periyar (river)|Periyar]] and the Cheruthoniar.<ref>http://www.forest.kerala.gov.in/index.php/wildlife/2015-03-16-09-50-24/2015-06-26-09-04-29/idukki-wildlife-sanctuary</ref>\n\n===Eravikulam Wild Life Sanctuary===\n[[File:Nilgiri Tahr Adult.jpg|thumb|250px|Nilagiri Tahr]]\n[[Eravikulam National Park|Eravikulam]] is another wildlife sanctuary proclaimed as a National Park. It supports the largest population of [[Nilgiri tahr]] in the world. Anamudi peak is on the southern part of this park.\nMost of the park is grassland and the average altitude is more than 5000 feet above [[Mean sea level|sea level]]. Heavy rain and gushing winds makes the area inaccessible during the monsoon season. The famous Neelakurinji ([[Strobilanthes kunthiana]]) grows here. It has a flowering cycle of 12 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/idukki.htm|title=Information and Public Relations Department, Govt. of Kerala|access-date=13 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228064818/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/idukki.htm|archive-date=28 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Twenty six species of [[mammals]] have been recorded in the park including the largest surviving population of [[Nilgiri tahr]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Munnar|url=http://www.keralatourism.org/destination/destination.php?id=306|access-date=22 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118183559/http://www.keralatourism.org/destination/destination.php?id=306|archive-date=18 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> estimated at about 750 individuals. The other [[ungulates]] are [[gaur]], [[Indian muntjac]] and [[sambar deer]]. [[Golden jackal]], [[jungle cat]], [[Dhole|wild dog]], [[dhole]], [[leopard]] and tiger are the main predators.  Some little-known animals such as [[Nilgiri langur]], [[stripe-necked mongoose]], [[Indian porcupine]], [[Nilgiri marten]], [[Oriental small-clawed otter|small clawed otter]], [[ruddy mongoose]], and [[Funambulus sublineatus|dusky palm squirrel]] are also found.<ref>UNEP (05/07/2007) World Commission on Protected Areas, World Database on Protected Areas, Eravikulam National Park, Retrieved 7 May 2007 {{cite web |url=http://sea.unep-wcmc.org/wdpa/sitedetails.cfm?siteid=700&level=nat |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929140736/http://sea.unep-wcmc.org/wdpa/sitedetails.cfm?siteid=700&level=nat |archive-date=29 September 2007  }}</ref> [[Indian elephant|Elephants]] make seasonal visits.\n\n132 species of birds have been recorded which include endemics like [[black-and-orange flycatcher]], [[Nilgiri pipit]], [[Nilgiri wood pigeon]], [[Brachypteryx major|white bellied shortwing]], [[Eumyias albicaudata|Nilgiri flycatcher]] and Kerala [[laughingthrush]].\n\nEndemic butterflies confined to the shola-grass land ecosystem like the [[Mycalesis oculus|red disk bushbrown]] and Palni four-wing are among the 101 species in the park.\n\n===Periyar Tiger Reserve===\n[[Periyar National Park|Periyar Tiger Reserve]], Thekkady, is sprawled over an area of 925&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. Periyar is one of the 50 tiger reserves in India. This zealously guarded and efficiently managed reserve is a repository of rare, endemic and endangered flora and fauna, and forms the major watershed of two important rivers of Kerala, the Periyar, and Pamba.\n[[File:Wild elephants, Munnar.jpg|thumb|Wild elephants in [[Munnar]], Kerala]]\n'''Periyar National Park and Wildlife Sanctuary''' (PNP) is a [[protected area]] in the districts of Idukki and Pathanamthitta in Kerala. It is notable as an [[Project Elephant|elephant reserve]] and a [[Project Tiger|tiger reserve]]. The protected area covers an area of {{convert|925|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}. {{convert|305|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} of the core zone was declared as the Periyar National Park in 1982\n\n===Pampadumshola National Park===\n[[Pampadum Shola National Park]] is the smallest [[National parks of India|national park]] in [[Kerala]] state, [[South India]].<ref name=\"envis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kerenvis.nic.in/isbeid/forest.htm |last=Envis Kerala |year=2009 |title=Forest |publisher=Kerala State Council for Science, Technology and Environment |access-date=18 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311001130/http://www.kerenvis.nic.in/isbeid/forest.htm |archive-date=11 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>Online Highways LLC. (2004) India | Kerala | Devikulam\nPambadum Shola National Park, Retrieved 6 April 2007 [http://www.india9.com/i9show/Pambadum-Shola-National-Park-57785.htm]</ref> The park is administered by the Kerala Department of Forests and Wildlife, Munnar Wildlife Division, together with the nearby [[Mathikettan Shola National Park]], [[Eravikulam National Park]], [[Anamudi Shola National Park]], [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]] and the [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]].<ref>K.S. Sudhi (3 November 2006) The Hindu, retrieved 21 June 2007 [http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/03/stories/2006110300820200.htm ''New lives bloom in Rajamala'']</ref> The park adjoins the Allinagaram Reserved Forest within the proposed [[Palani Hills Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]]. The Western Ghats, Anamalai Sub-Cluster, including these parks, is under consideration by the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site#World Heritage Committee Session|World Heritage Committee]] for selection as a [[World Heritage Site]].<ref name=\"UNESCO\" >UNESCO, World Heritage sites, Tentative lists, Western Ghats sub cluster, Niligiris. retrieved 20 April 2007 [https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2103/ World Heritage sites, Tentative lists]</ref>\n\n===Kurinjimala Sanctuary===\n[[File:Strobilanths kunthiana.jpg|thumb|[[Neelakurinji]]]]\n[[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] protects the approximately 32&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> core habitat of the endangered [[Neelakurinji]] plant in [[Kottakamboor]] and [[Vattavada]] villages in [[Devikulam]] Taluk, Idukki district of [[Kerala]] State in [[South India]].<ref>[http://kurinji.in/kurinjimap.html map]</ref>\n\n===Protected areas===\n[[File:GrizzledSquirell-cauvery wls.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Giant grizzled squirrel]]\nThis district has several [[Protected areas of Kerala|protected areas]] including: [[Periyar Tiger Reserve]] in the south, [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]] to the east, [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]] to the northeast, [[Eravikulam National Park]] and [[Anamudi Shola National Park]] to the north and [[Pampadum Shola National Park]] to the south.  These protected areas are well known for several [[threatened]] and [[Endemism|endemic]] species including [[Bengal tiger|tiger]], [[Nilgiri tahr]], [[grizzled giant squirrel]], [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], [[Indian elephant|elephant]], gaur, sambar deer, [[purple frog]] and [[neelakurinji]].<ref>Government of Kerala, Forest and Wildlife Department, Notification No. 36/2006 F&WLD (6 October 2006) Retrieved 5 December 2007 [http://kurinji.in/sro.html Kerala Gazette]</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mathew |last=Roy |date=25 September 2006 |title=Proposal for Kurinjimala sanctuary awaits Cabinet nod |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=5 December 2007 |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/09/25/stories/2006092510910400.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Waterfalls==\nThere are several waterfalls in Idukki, most of them are active only during the monsoon season.\n\n===Cheeyappara===\nThe [[Cheeyappara Waterfalls]]('''\u0d1a\u0d40\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d31''') is on the [[Kochi, India|Kochi]] \u2013 [[Madurai]] Highway in Idukki district ([[National Highway 49 (India)|National Highway 49]]), between [[Neriamangalam]] and [[Adimali]]. The Cheeyappara Waterfall cascades down in seven steps. This place is well known for trekking.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===Thommankuthu===\n[[File:Thommankuthu waterfalls.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thommankuthu Waterfalls]]\n'''[[Thommankuthu]] (\u0d24\u0d4a\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d7b\u0d15\u0d41\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d4d)''' is a scenic waterfall near [[Thodupuzha]] in the district. Thomankoothu waterfalls is not a single waterfall but a series of 12 falls over a distance of 5km.<ref>http://www.forest.kerala.gov.in/index.php/idukki/thommankuthu-eco-tourism</ref> It is one of the major eco-tourism centers in Idukki, Kerala.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n{{Main|Administration of Idukki district}}\n[[File:Thodupuzha Civil Station.jpg|thumb|right|Thodupuzha Civil Station]]\nIdukki District is divided into eight community development blocks (block panchayats).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory: Block Panchayats of Idukki, Kerala |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj, Government of India|url=}}</ref> The community development blocks are further divided into [[taluka]]s. The blocks are:<ref>{{Cite web|title=Idukki Zilla Panchayat|url=http://idukki.nic.in/local.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209003839/http://www.idukki.nic.in/local.htm |archive-date=9 December 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* Adimaly Block \n* Azhutha Block \n* Devikulam Block\n* Elamdesom Block \n* Idukki Block \n* Kattappana Block \n* Nedumkandam Block\n* Thodupuzha Block \n}}\n\n===Municipalities===\n* [[Thodupuzha]]\n* [[Kattappana]]\n\n===Towns===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Thodupuzha|Thodupuzha (TDPA)]]\n* [[Kattappana|Kattappana (KTPNA)]]\n* [[Adimali]]\n* [[Munnar|Munnar (MNR)]]\n* [[Devikulam]]\n* [[Chinnakanal]]\n* [[Rajakkad]]\n* [[Rajakumari, Idukki district|Rajakumari]]\n* [[Udumbanchola]]\n* [[Nedumkandam|Nedumkandam (NDKM)]]\n* [[Anakkara (Idukki)|Anakkara]]\n* [[Idukki township|Idukki]]\n** [[Cheruthoni]]\n** [[Mannathara]]\n** Mariyapuram\n** Keerithode\n** Kanjikuzhy\n** [[Murickassery]]\n* [[Thopramkudy]]\n* [[Moolamattom|Moolamattom (MLTM)]]\n** [[Muttom, Thodupuzha|Muttom]]\n* [[Karimannoor]]\n*[[Vannappuram]]\n* [[Peruvanthanam]]\n* [[Peerumedu]]\n** [[Kuttikkanam]]\n* [[Upputhara]]\n* [[Elappara]]\n* [[Wagamon]]\n* [[Vandiperiyar]]\n* [[Kumily|Kumily (KMLY)]]\n** [[Thekkady]]\n\n}}\n\n===Borders===\n* Cumbummettu\n* [[Kumily]]\n\n==Culture==\nCulture in Idukki is mixed since it constitutes of migrated people from other parts of [[Kerala]] and native tribals. The presence of a large number of tribal populations is peculiar to Idukki District. [[Kozhimala|Kovilmala]], near Kattappana in Idukki is home to one of the still ruling tribal kings in India, Kovilmala Raja Mannan.[[Kozhimala|Kovilmala]] is the headquarters of Mannan community who preserves certain customs, traditions, and form of governance, making them a unique tribal unit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/young-tribal-king-dies-of-heart-attack/article2756552.ece|title=Young tribal king dies of heart attack|last=Correspondent|first=A|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> The system of governance here is a [[Democracy|democratic]] - [[monarchy]] in which a king is elected by the people to rule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alienadv.com/activityDetails/3561/A-Day-with-Mannans-of-Kovilamala-Kingdom-Kerala/|title=A Day with Mannans of Kovilamala Kingdom Kerala|newspaper=www.alienadv.com|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIndigenous art forms in Idukki are not as popular as other major art forms. Tourist areas like [[Munnar]] and Thekkady welcome people by hosting popular art forms like [[Kathakali]].\n\n==Dams in Idukki==\n{{See also|SNC-Lavalin Kerala hydroelectric scandal}}\n[[File:Idukki arch Dam view 155706.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Idukki arch Dam]]\nThe first and oldest dam in Kerala is [[Mullaperiyar]]. It was inaugurated in 1895. The largest dam in Kerala is [[Idukki Dam]].It was built in 1955.\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Idukki Dam|Idukki Arch-Dam]]\n*[[Cheruthoni Dam|Cheruthoni]]\n*[[Mullaperiyar Dam|Mullapperiyar]]\n*[[Ponmudi Dam|Ponmudy]]\n*Kallarkutty Dam\n*Kundala Dam\n* Mattuppetti\n*Aanayirangal Dam\n*[[Bhoothathankettu]]\n*Sengulam Dam\n*Lower Periyar Dam\n*[[Malankara Dam|Malankara]]\n*Kallar Dam (Nedumkandam)\n*[[Kulamavu Dam|Kulamavu]]\n*Munnar Head Works\n*Erattayar Dam\n*Uluppuni Dam\n*Kochu Pamba\n}}\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\nThe roads in Idukki are part of Ghat roads. The major roads connect the city of [[Kochi]] to Tamil Nadu. The KK road (Kumili-Kottayam), the PT road (Puliyanmala-Thodupuzha State Highway-33) are some of the other busy roads.\n\n====Neriamangalam Bridge====\nThe [[Neriamangalam]] Bridge, built across the Periyar river, is often referred to as 'The Gateway to the Highranges' as it is on the way to the higher regions of Idukki district, especially Munnar. The bridge was made by the [[List of Maharajas of Travancore|Maharaja of Travancore]] in 1935.\n[[File:Neriamangalam bridge.PNG|thumb|right|Neryamangalam bridge]]\n\n===Rail===\nAt present, there is no railway in and to Idukki district of Kerala. The nearest railway stations are Kottayam (station code \u2013 KTYM), Aluva (Alwaye, station code \u2013 AWY), Ernakulam South (Ernakulam Jn., station code \u2013 ERS) and Ernakulam North (Ernakulam Town, station code \u2013 ERN).\n\n===Air===\nThe nearest airport to Idukki is [[Cochin International Airport]] and [[Coimbatore Airport]]. [[Airport Authority of India]]'s plan to set up an airport in Anakkara is in a conflict of environmental issues. Anakkara Airport will be a great leap in Idukki's complete development. The government claims this project will improve the tourism in the area. However, with Anakkara being situated in environmentally sensitive [[Western Ghats]], environmentalists and villagers argue that this can significantly impact the area's climatic conditions and livelihood of people. Also, the land identified for the project is one of the very few remaining paddy fields of the district, currently cultivating some of the rare indigenous varieties of rice which increases the concern about the project. Those opposing the airport also cite the economic benefits as Munnar, one of the key target destinations for the airport lies at about 100&nbsp;km from Anakkara and the time taken to reach there from [[Cochin International Airport]] is less than the time taken to reach from Anakkara.  Though there are no clear references online from the government on the objectives, benefits, and purpose of the proposed airport, anti-Anakkara-airport groups have set up social networking campaign sites explaining reasons why they claim the airport project should not be implemented.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Trissur district]]\n*[[Civil Station, Idukki]]\n*[[Keezhanthoor]]\n*[[Santhanpara]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Idukki district}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130724132707/http://www.idukki.nic.in/ Official Idukki District website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080531154944/http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl1813/18130780.htm Human Development Index (HDI) and Gender Development Index (GDI)]\n* {{curlie|Regional/Asia/India/Kerala/Districts/Idukki/}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Idukki district\n| North     = [[Coimbatore district]], Tamil Nadu\n| Northeast = {{ubl|[[Coimbatore district]], Tamil Nadu| [[Tiruppur district]], Tamil Nadu | [[Dindigul district]], Tamil Nadu}}\n| East      = [[Theni district]], Tamil Nadu\n| Southeast = {{ubl|[[Virudhunagar district]], Tamil Nadu | [[Tirunelveli district]], Tamil Nadu}}\n| South     = [[Pathanamthitta district]]\n| Southwest =\n| West      = [[Kottayam district]]\n| Northwest = [[Ernakulam district]]\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles Related to Idukki\n| list  =\n{{Kerala}}\n{{Northern Travancore}}\n{{Idukki district}}\n{{Hindu temples in Kerala}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idukki}}\n[[Category:Districts of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Idukki district| ]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTelugu(link changed toTelugu language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idukki_district"}
{"title_page": "Private Internet Access", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{short description|Virtual private network service}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Private Internet Access\n| logo = Private Internet Access Black Logo with no Tagline.svg\n| logo size = 240px\n| screenshot = Private Internet Access iOS client.jpg\n| caption = iOS client\n| collapsible = y\n| developer = Kape Technologies\n| released = August 2010\n| repo = {{URL|https://github.com/pia-foss}}\n| operating system = {{flatlist|\n* [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n* [[iOS]]\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[macOS]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n}}\n| size = \n| language = English\n| license = {{plainlist|\n* '''Desktop client:''' [[GPLv3]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/pia-foss/desktop/blob/master/LICENSE.txt|title=desktop/LICENSE.txt at master \u00b7 pia-foss/desktop|date=17 December 2019|access-date=18 December 2019|website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n* '''iOS client:''' [[MIT License]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/pia-foss/vpn-ios/blob/master/LICENSE|date=11 April 2018|access-date=18 December 2019|title=vpn-ios/LICENSE at master \u00b7 pia-foss/vpn-ios|website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n* '''Android client:''' [[Commercial software|Commercial]] [[proprietary software]]\n}}\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| genre = [[Virtual private network]]\n}}\t\n'''Private Internet Access''' ('''PIA''') is an open source personal [[virtual private network]] (VPN) service. It supports multiple VPN technologies such as [[PPTP]], [[L2TP]]/[[IPsec]], [[SOCKS5]] and [[OpenVPN]]. In 2018, former [[Mt. Gox]] CEO  [[Mark Karpel\u00e8s]] was named chief technology officer of PIA's parent company, London Trust Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/mt-gox-bitcoin-exchange-former-ceo-karpeles-lands-new-job/|title=Former Mt. Gox bitcoin exchange CEO Karpeles lands new job|last=Goldman|first=Joshua|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Private Internet Access was acquired by Kape Technologies.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak acquisition\">{{cite web |last1=Van Der Sar |first1=Ernesto |title=Private Internet Access to Be Acquired by Kape |url=https://torrentfreak.com/private-internet-access-to-be-acquired-by-kape/ |website=TorrentFreak |accessdate=28 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128214936/https://torrentfreak.com/private-internet-access-to-be-acquired-by-kape/ |archivedate=28 November 2019 |language=en |date=24 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Company==\n\nThe CEO of Private Internet Access (and its parent company, London Trust Media, Inc.) is Ted Kim. The company was founded by the American-born [[Andrew Lee (entrepreneur)|Andrew Lee]], who has been named the official successor to the throne of the [[House of Yi]] (Lee), the ruling former house of the [[Joseon dynasty]]. Lee, who dropped out of college before graduating, started his own online business which eventually became Private Internet Access.<ref>https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/people/article/2175439/no-k-drama-fresh-prince-south-korea-real-royalty-and-hes-american</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/10/how-one-small-american-vpn-company-is-trying-to-stand-up-for-privacy/|title=How one small American VPN company is trying to stand up for privacy|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-us}}</ref> London Trust Media also owns the [[Freenode]] [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freenode.net/news/pia-fn|title=PIA and freenode joining forces - freenode|website=freenode.net|language=en|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2019, Private Internet Access announced that it would be merged into Kape Technologies, which operates two competing VPN services, [[Cyberghost]] and [[Zenmate]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-12-18|title=Bellum Omnium Contra Omnes (\u201cThe War of All Against All\u201d)|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/blog/2019/11/bellum-omnium-contra-omnes-the-war-of-all-against-all/|website=Private Internet Access Blog|date=18 November 2019|first=Andrew|last=Lee}}</ref> Some users objected to the acquisition, as Kape (under its former name, Crossrider) previously developed [[browser toolbar]]s bundled with [[potentially unwanted program]]s.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak acquisition\" />\n\n== Technical info ==\nPIA offers several features, including [[DNS leak]] protection and [[IPv6]] leak protection. It includes a connection kill switch to prevent traffic going elsewhere when VPN gets disconnected. It is possible to access services via [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]] and [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]. PIA offers also unlimited [[bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] and [[Port forwarding]]. They operate VPN gateways in 54 regions across 33 countries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=London Trust Media, Inc.|title=Private Internet Access Anonymous VPN|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/pages/network/|website=www.privateinternetaccess.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Encryption ===\nPrivate Internet Access supports the [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] (128-bit or 256-bit) specifications, SHA1 and SHA256 authentication, and  [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] (2048, 3072, 4096) or [[Elliptic curve cryptography|elliptic curve cryptography (ECC)]] (256R1, 256K1, 521) handshakes; however, the default settings are AES-128, SHA1, RSA-2048.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Private Internet Access Anonymous VPN |url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/pages/vpn-encryption |publisher=London Trust Media |access-date=2017-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Comparison of virtual private network services]]\n* [[Linux Journal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{VPN}}\n\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Virtual private network services]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{short description|Virtual private network service}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Private Internet Access\n| logo = Private Internet Access Black Logo with no Tagline.svg\n| logo size = 240px\n| screenshot = Private Internet Access iOS client.jpg\n| caption = iOS client\n| collapsible = y\n| developer = Kape Technologies\n| released = August 2010\n| repo = {{URL|https://github.com/pia-foss}}\n| operating system = {{flatlist|\n* [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n* [[iOS]]\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[macOS]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n}}\n| size = \n| language = English\n| license = {{plainlist|\n* '''Desktop client:''' [[GPLv3]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/pia-foss/desktop/blob/master/LICENSE.txt|title=desktop/LICENSE.txt at master \u00b7 pia-foss/desktop|date=17 December 2019|access-date=18 December 2019|website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n* '''iOS client:''' [[MIT License]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/pia-foss/vpn-ios/blob/master/LICENSE|date=11 April 2018|access-date=18 December 2019|title=vpn-ios/LICENSE at master \u00b7 pia-foss/vpn-ios|website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref>\n* '''Android client:''' [[Commercial software|Commercial]] [[proprietary software]]\n}}\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| genre = [[Virtual private network]]\n}}\t\n'''Private Internet Access''' ('''PIA''') is an open source personal [[virtual private network]] (VPN) service. It supports multiple VPN technologies such as [[PPTP]], [[L2TP]]/[[IPsec]], [[SOCKS5]] and [[OpenVPN]]. In 2018, former [[Mt. Gox]] CEO  [[Mark Karpel\u00e8s]] was named chief technology officer of PIA's parent company, London Trust Media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/mt-gox-bitcoin-exchange-former-ceo-karpeles-lands-new-job/|title=Former Mt. Gox bitcoin exchange CEO Karpeles lands new job|last=Goldman|first=Joshua|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Private Internet Access was acquired by Kape Technologies.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak acquisition\">{{cite web |last1=Van Der Sar |first1=Ernesto |title=Private Internet Access to Be Acquired by Kape |url=https://torrentfreak.com/private-internet-access-to-be-acquired-by-kape/ |website=TorrentFreak |accessdate=28 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128214936/https://torrentfreak.com/private-internet-access-to-be-acquired-by-kape/ |archivedate=28 November 2019 |language=en |date=24 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Company==\n\nThe CEO of Private Internet Access (and its parent company, London Trust Media, Inc.) is Ted Kim. The company was founded by the American-born [[Andrew Lee (entrepreneur)|Andrew Lee]], who has been named the official successor to the thrown of the [[House of Yi]] (Lee), the ruling former house of the [[Joseon dynasty]]. Lee, who dropped out of college before graduating, started his own online business which eventually became Private Internet Access.<ref>https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/people/article/2175439/no-k-drama-fresh-prince-south-korea-real-royalty-and-hes-american</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/10/how-one-small-american-vpn-company-is-trying-to-stand-up-for-privacy/|title=How one small American VPN company is trying to stand up for privacy|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-us}}</ref> London Trust Media also owns the [[Freenode]] [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freenode.net/news/pia-fn|title=PIA and freenode joining forces - freenode|website=freenode.net|language=en|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn November 18, 2019, Private Internet Access announced that it would be merged into Kape Technologies, which operates two competing VPN services, [[Cyberghost]] and [[Zenmate]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-12-18|title=Bellum Omnium Contra Omnes (\u201cThe War of All Against All\u201d)|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/blog/2019/11/bellum-omnium-contra-omnes-the-war-of-all-against-all/|website=Private Internet Access Blog|date=18 November 2019|first=Andrew|last=Lee}}</ref> Some users objected to the acquisition, as Kape (under its former name, Crossrider) previously developed [[browser toolbar]]s bundled with [[potentially unwanted program]]s.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak acquisition\" />\n\n== Technical info ==\nPIA offers several features, including [[DNS leak]] protection and [[IPv6]] leak protection. It includes a connection kill switch to prevent traffic going elsewhere when VPN gets disconnected. It is possible to access services via [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]] and [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]. PIA offers also unlimited [[bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]] and [[Port forwarding]]. They operate VPN gateways in 54 regions across 33 countries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=London Trust Media, Inc.|title=Private Internet Access Anonymous VPN|url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/pages/network/|website=www.privateinternetaccess.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Encryption ===\nPrivate Internet Access supports the [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] (128-bit or 256-bit) specifications, SHA1 and SHA256 authentication, and  [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] (2048, 3072, 4096) or [[Elliptic curve cryptography|elliptic curve cryptography (ECC)]] (256R1, 256K1, 521) handshakes; however, the default settings are AES-128, SHA1, RSA-2048.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Private Internet Access Anonymous VPN |url=https://www.privateinternetaccess.com/pages/vpn-encryption |publisher=London Trust Media |access-date=2017-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Comparison of virtual private network services]]\n* [[Linux Journal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{VPN}}\n\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Virtual private network services]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2010]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "LuckyDucko", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCompany:Thrown -> throne spelling update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Private_Internet_Access"}
{"title_page": "Albizia lebbeck", "text_new": ":\"Mimosa speciosa\"'' redirects here. As described by [[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin]] this refers to ''Albizia lebbeck''. The ''Mimosa speciosa'' of [[Carl Peter Thunberg]], however, is ''Albizia julibrissin''.\n__NOTOC__\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr_080531-4752_Albizia_lebbeck.jpg\n|genus = Albizia\n|species = lebbeck\n|authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]) [[Benth.]]\n|synonyms = Many, see [[#Taxonomy|text]]\n}}\n\n'''''Albizia lebbeck''''' is a [[species]] of ''[[Albizia]]'', native to [[Indomalaya ecozone|Indomalaya]], [[New Guinea]] and [[Northern Australia]]<ref name=\"USDA 1994\">USDA (1994)</ref><ref>Lowry, J.B. & Seebeck, J. 1997 \"The Potential for Tropical Agroforestry in Wood and Animal Feed Production\". Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation, Indooroopilly, Queensland</ref> and widely cultivated and [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]] in other [[tropical]] and [[subtropical]] regions. English names for it include '''lebbeck''', '''lebbek tree''', '''flea tree''', '''frywood''', '''koko''' and '''woman's tongue tree'''. The latter name is a play on the sound the seeds make as they rattle inside the pods. Being one of the most widespread and common species of ''Albizia'' worldwide, it is often simply called '''siris''', though this name may refer to any locally common member of the [[genus]].<ref name=\"USDA 1994\"/>\n\nIt is a [[tree]] growing to a height of 18\u201330 m tall with a trunk 50&nbsp;cm to 1 m in diameter. The [[leaf|leaves]] are bipinnate, 7.5\u201315&nbsp;cm long, with one to four pairs of pinnae, each pinna with 6\u201318 leaflets. The [[flower]]s are white, with numerous 2.5\u20133.8&nbsp;cm long stamens, and very fragrant. The [[fruit]] is a [[legume|pod]] 15\u201330&nbsp;cm long and 2.5-5.0&nbsp;cm broad, containing six to twelve [[seed]]s.<ref>Ali (1973)</ref>\n\nIn the [[West Indies]] and certain parts of [[South America]] this tree is known as a 'Shak Shak Tree' because of the sound the seeds make in the pod.\nIn [[Tamil Nadu]] , the tree is known as 'vaagai' as the ancient kings of the [[Sangam  Age]] had worn the garland made by this flower whenever they win battles . Similarly , 'vaagai' means 'victory' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]].\n\n== Uses ==\n[[Image:Bark of Albizia lebbeck.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Bark of ''Albizia lebbeck'']]\nIts uses include environmental management,  [[Fodder|forage]], medicine and wood.  It is cultivated as a shade tree in [[North America|North]] and [[South America]].<ref name = ildis>ILDIS (2005)</ref> In India and Pakistan, the tree is used to produce [[timber]]. Wood from ''Albizia lebbeck'' has a density of 0.55-0.66 g/cm<sup>3</sup> or higher.<ref>Brown (1997)</ref>\n\nEven where it is not native, some indigenous [[herbivore]]s are liable to utilize lebbeck as a food resource. For example, the [[greater rhea]] (''Rhea americana'') has been observed feeding on it in the [[cerrado]] of [[Brazil]].<ref>Schetini de Azevedo ''et al.'' (2006)</ref>\n\n===Ethnobotany===\nLebbeck is an [[astringent]], also used by some cultures to treat boils, [[cough]], to treat the [[human eye|eye]], [[flu]], [[gingivitis]], [[human lung|lung]] problems, pectoral problems, is used as a tonic, and is used to treat abdominal [[tumor]]s.<ref>Duke (2008)</ref> The bark is used medicinally to treat [[inflammation]].<ref>Lowry ''et al.''(1994)</ref> This information was obtained via [[ethnobotany|ethnobotanical records]], which are a reference to how a plant is used by indigenous peoples, not verifiable, scientific or medical evaluation of the effectiveness of these claims. ''Albizia lebbeck'' is also [[psychoactive]].<ref>R\u00e4tsch (2004)</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] history of ''A. lebbeck'' is somewhat convoluted. It was originally described by [[Carl Linnaeus]] as ''Mimosa lebbeck''. [[George Bentham]] placed the [[species]] in its present [[genus]], but other authors believed that the plant described by Linnaeus was the related ''[[Albizia kalkora]]'' as described by Prain (based on the ''Mimosa kalkora'' of [[William Roxburgh]]), and erroneously referred to this species as ''Albizia lebbeck''. However, [[Francisco Manuel Blanco]] used ''Mimosa lebbeck'' to refer to ''[[Albizia retusa]]'' ssp. ''retusa''. In addition, the [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] is occasionally misspelled ''lebbek''.<ref>USDA (1994), ILDIS (2005)</ref>\n\n[[Junior synonym]]s are:<ref name = ildis />\n* ''Acacia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) [[Willd.]]</small>\n* ''Acacia macrophylla'' <small>[[Alexander G. von Bunge|Bunge]]</small>\n* ''Acacia speciosa'' <small>(Jacq.) Willd.</small>\n* ''Albizia latifolia'' <small>B.Boivin</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''leucoxylon'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''pubescens'' <small>Haines</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''rostrata'' <small>Haines</small>\n:''Albizia rostrata'' <small>Miq.</small> is ''[[Archidendron globosum]]''.\n* ''Feuilleea lebbeck'' <small>(L.) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>\n* ''Inga borbonica'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Inga leucoxylon'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Mimosa lebbeck'' <small>L.</small>\n* ''Mimosa lebbek'' <small>L. (orth.var.)</small>\n* ''Mimosa sirissa'' <small>Roxb.</small>\n* ''Mimosa speciosa'' <small>[[Jacq.]]</small>\n:''Mimosa speciosa'' <small>Thunb.</small> is ''[[Albizia julibrissin]]''.\n* ''Pithecellobium splitgerberianum'' <small>[[Miq.]]</small>\n\nThere also exists a genus named ''[[Lebeckia]]'', in reference to the lebbeck. It is not closely related to ''A. lebeck'' however, but a member of the [[Faboideae]], a different legume [[subfamily]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{aut|Ali, S.I.}} (1973): ''Albizia lebbeck'' (L.) Benth.. ''In: Flora of Pakistan'' (Vol. 36: Mimosaceae). University of Karachi, Karachi. [http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=5&taxon_id=200011877 HTML fulltext]\n* {{aut|Brown, Sandra}} (1997): Appendix 1 - List of wood densities for tree species from tropical America, Africa, and Asia. ''In:'' Estimating Biomass and Biomass Change of Tropical Forests: a Primer. ''FAO Forestry Papers'' '''134'''. <small>{{ISBN|92-5-103955-0}}</small> [http://www.fao.org/docrep/W4095E/w4095e0c.htm HTML fulltext]\n* {{aut|Duke, James A.}} (2008): Dr. Duke's Phytochemical and Ethnobotanical Databases - [https://phytochem.nal.usda.gov/phytochem/plants/show/2323?qlookup=Albizia+lebbeck&offset=0&max=20&et= ''Albizia lebbeck'']. Retrieved 2008-FEB-23.\n* {{aut|International Legume Database & Information Service (ILDIS)}} (2005): [http://www.ildis.org/LegumeWeb?version~10.01&LegumeWeb&tno~184&genus~Albizia&species~lebbeck ''Albizia lebbeck'' (L.) Benth.]. Version 10.01, November 2005. Retrieved 2008-MAR-30.\n* {{aut|Lowry, J.B.; Prinsen, J.H. & Burrows,  D.M.}} (1994): 2.5 Albizia lebbeck - a Promising Forage Tree for Semiarid Regions. ''In:'' {{aut|Gutteridge, Ross C. & Shelton, H. Max (eds.)}}: ''Forage Tree Legumes in Tropical Agriculture''. CAB Intemational. [http://www.fao.org/ag/agP/agpc/doc/Publicat/Gutt-shel/x5556e0a.htm HTML fulltext]\n* {{aut|R\u00e4tsch, Christian}} (2004): ''Enzyklop\u00e4die der psychoaktiven Pflanzen, Botanik, Ethnopharmakologie und Anwendungen'' (7th ed.). AT Verlag. <small>{{ISBN|3-85502-570-3}}</small>\n* {{aut|Schetini de Azevedo, Cristiano; Penha Tinoco, Herlandes; Bosco Ferraz, Jo\u00e3o & Young, Robert John}} (2006): The fishing rhea: a new food item in the diet of wild greater rheas (''Rhea americana'', Rheidae, Aves). ''Revista Brasileira de Ornitologia'' '''14'''(3): 285-287 [English with Portuguese abstract]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20081219192103/http://www.ararajuba.org.br/sbo/ararajuba/artigos/Volume143/ara143not3.pdf PDF fulltext]\n* {{aut|[[United States Department of Agriculture]] (USDA)}} (1994): Germplasm Resources Information Network - [https://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/taxon.pl?2140 ''Albizia lebbeck'' (L.) Benth.]. Version of 1994-AUG-23. Retrieved 2008-MAR-30.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Albizia lebbeck}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041118072159/http://sun.ars-grin.gov:8080/npgspub/xsql/duke/plantdisp.xsql?taxon=2361 ''Albizia lebbeck'' List of Chemicals (Dr. Duke's Databases)]\n* {{AfricanPlants|Albizia lebbeck}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2717846}}\n\n[[Category:Albizia|lebbeck]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of Oceania]]\n[[Category:Forages]]\n[[Category:Flora of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Bushfood]]\n[[Category:Trees of India]]\n[[Category:Trees of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Trees of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n", "text_old": ":\"Mimosa speciosa\"'' redirects here. As described by [[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin]] this refers to ''Albizia lebbeck''. The ''Mimosa speciosa'' of [[Carl Peter Thunberg]], however, is ''Albizia julibrissin''.\n__NOTOC__\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr_080531-4752_Albizia_lebbeck.jpg\n|genus = Albizia\n|species = lebbeck\n|authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]) [[Benth.]]\n|synonyms = Many, see [[#Taxonomy|text]]\n}}\n\n'''''Albizia lebbeck''''' is a [[species]] of ''[[Albizia]]'', native to [[Indomalaya ecozone|Indomalaya]], [[New Guinea]] and [[Northern Australia]]<ref name=\"USDA 1994\">USDA (1994)</ref><ref>Lowry, J.B. & Seebeck, J. 1997 \"The Potential for Tropical Agroforestry in Wood and Animal Feed Production\". Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation, Indooroopilly, Queensland</ref> and widely cultivated and [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]] in other [[tropical]] and [[subtropical]] regions. English names for it include '''lebbeck''', '''lebbek tree''', '''flea tree''', '''frywood''', '''koko''' and '''woman's tongue tree'''. The latter name is a play on the sound the seeds make as they rattle inside the pods. Being one of the most widespread and common species of ''Albizia'' worldwide, it is often simply called '''siris''', though this name may refer to any locally common member of the [[genus]].<ref name=\"USDA 1994\"/>\n\nIt is a [[tree]] growing to a height of 18\u201330 m tall with a trunk 50&nbsp;cm to 1 m in diameter. The [[leaf|leaves]] are bipinnate, 7.5\u201315&nbsp;cm long, with one to four pairs of pinnae, each pinna with 6\u201318 leaflets. The [[flower]]s are white, with numerous 2.5\u20133.8&nbsp;cm long stamens, and very fragrant. The [[fruit]] is a [[legume|pod]] 15\u201330&nbsp;cm long and 2.5-5.0&nbsp;cm broad, containing six to twelve [[seed]]s.<ref>Ali (1973)</ref>\n\nIn the [[West Indies]] and certain parts of [[South America]] this tree is known as a 'Shak Shak Tree' because of the sound the seeds make in the pod.\nIn [[Tamil Nadu]] , the tree is known as 'vaagai' as the ancient kings of the [[Sangam  Age]] had worn the garland made by this flower whenever they win battles . Similarly , 'vaagai' means 'victory' in [[Tamil]].\n\n== Uses ==\n[[Image:Bark of Albizia lebbeck.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Bark of ''Albizia lebbeck'']]\nIts uses include environmental management,  [[Fodder|forage]], medicine and wood.  It is cultivated as a shade tree in [[North America|North]] and [[South America]].<ref name = ildis>ILDIS (2005)</ref> In India and Pakistan, the tree is used to produce [[timber]]. Wood from ''Albizia lebbeck'' has a density of 0.55-0.66 g/cm<sup>3</sup> or higher.<ref>Brown (1997)</ref>\n\nEven where it is not native, some indigenous [[herbivore]]s are liable to utilize lebbeck as a food resource. For example, the [[greater rhea]] (''Rhea americana'') has been observed feeding on it in the [[cerrado]] of [[Brazil]].<ref>Schetini de Azevedo ''et al.'' (2006)</ref>\n\n===Ethnobotany===\nLebbeck is an [[astringent]], also used by some cultures to treat boils, [[cough]], to treat the [[human eye|eye]], [[flu]], [[gingivitis]], [[human lung|lung]] problems, pectoral problems, is used as a tonic, and is used to treat abdominal [[tumor]]s.<ref>Duke (2008)</ref> The bark is used medicinally to treat [[inflammation]].<ref>Lowry ''et al.''(1994)</ref> This information was obtained via [[ethnobotany|ethnobotanical records]], which are a reference to how a plant is used by indigenous peoples, not verifiable, scientific or medical evaluation of the effectiveness of these claims. ''Albizia lebbeck'' is also [[psychoactive]].<ref>R\u00e4tsch (2004)</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] history of ''A. lebbeck'' is somewhat convoluted. It was originally described by [[Carl Linnaeus]] as ''Mimosa lebbeck''. [[George Bentham]] placed the [[species]] in its present [[genus]], but other authors believed that the plant described by Linnaeus was the related ''[[Albizia kalkora]]'' as described by Prain (based on the ''Mimosa kalkora'' of [[William Roxburgh]]), and erroneously referred to this species as ''Albizia lebbeck''. However, [[Francisco Manuel Blanco]] used ''Mimosa lebbeck'' to refer to ''[[Albizia retusa]]'' ssp. ''retusa''. In addition, the [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] is occasionally misspelled ''lebbek''.<ref>USDA (1994), ILDIS (2005)</ref>\n\n[[Junior synonym]]s are:<ref name = ildis />\n* ''Acacia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) [[Willd.]]</small>\n* ''Acacia macrophylla'' <small>[[Alexander G. von Bunge|Bunge]]</small>\n* ''Acacia speciosa'' <small>(Jacq.) Willd.</small>\n* ''Albizia latifolia'' <small>B.Boivin</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''leucoxylon'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''pubescens'' <small>Haines</small>\n* ''Albizia lebbeck'' <small>(L.) Benth.</small> var. ''rostrata'' <small>Haines</small>\n:''Albizia rostrata'' <small>Miq.</small> is ''[[Archidendron globosum]]''.\n* ''Feuilleea lebbeck'' <small>(L.) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small>\n* ''Inga borbonica'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Inga leucoxylon'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Mimosa lebbeck'' <small>L.</small>\n* ''Mimosa lebbek'' <small>L. (orth.var.)</small>\n* ''Mimosa sirissa'' <small>Roxb.</small>\n* ''Mimosa speciosa'' <small>[[Jacq.]]</small>\n:''Mimosa speciosa'' <small>Thunb.</small> is ''[[Albizia julibrissin]]''.\n* ''Pithecellobium splitgerberianum'' <small>[[Miq.]]</small>\n\nThere also exists a genus named ''[[Lebeckia]]'', in reference to the lebbeck. It is not closely related to ''A. lebeck'' however, but a member of the [[Faboideae]], a different legume [[subfamily]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{aut|Ali, S.I.}} (1973): ''Albizia lebbeck'' (L.) Benth.. ''In: Flora of Pakistan'' (Vol. 36: Mimosaceae). University of Karachi, Karachi. [http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=5&taxon_id=200011877 HTML fulltext]\n* {{aut|Brown, Sandra}} (1997): Appendix 1 - List of wood densities for tree species from tropical America, Africa, and Asia. ''In:'' Estimating Biomass and Biomass Change of Tropical Forests: a Primer. ''FAO Forestry Papers'' '''134'''. <small>{{ISBN|92-5-103955-0}}</small> [http://www.fao.org/docrep/W4095E/w4095e0c.htm HTML fulltext]\n* {{aut|Duke, James A.}} (2008): Dr. Duke's Phytochemical and Ethnobotanical Databases - [https://phytochem.nal.usda.gov/phytochem/plants/show/2323?qlookup=Albizia+lebbeck&offset=0&max=20&et= ''Albizia lebbeck'']. Retrieved 2008-FEB-23.\n* {{aut|International Legume Database & Information Service (ILDIS)}} (2005): [http://www.ildis.org/LegumeWeb?version~10.01&LegumeWeb&tno~184&genus~Albizia&species~lebbeck ''Albizia lebbeck'' (L.) Benth.]. Version 10.01, November 2005. Retrieved 2008-MAR-30.\n* {{aut|Lowry, J.B.; Prinsen, J.H. & Burrows,  D.M.}} (1994): 2.5 Albizia lebbeck - a Promising Forage Tree for Semiarid Regions. ''In:'' {{aut|Gutteridge, Ross C. & Shelton, H. Max (eds.)}}: ''Forage Tree Legumes in Tropical Agriculture''. CAB Intemational. [http://www.fao.org/ag/agP/agpc/doc/Publicat/Gutt-shel/x5556e0a.h